&#xa0;
[normal]Cabinet Office[bold] – Written evidence[bold]&#xa0;[bold]DELEGATED POWERS AND REGULATORY REFORM COMMITTEE[bold]DRAFT DEREGULATION BILL[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Introduction [bold]&#xa0;[bold]1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This Memorandum has been prepared for the Joint Committee which is scrutinising the Deregulation Bill in draft form (‘the Bill’) and for the consideration of the Delegated Powers and Regulatory Reform Committee. 
[normal]2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The memorandum identifies the provisions of the Bill which confer powers to make delegated legislation. It explains in each case why the power has been taken and the nature of, and reason for, the procedure selected. 
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Since the Bill deals with diverse subject areas, and covers changes from a number of departments, each measure is addressed individually. Most powers are specific to individual clauses but the Bill also includes some general powers. The material for the Memorandum was prepared by the relevant departments and drawn together by the Cabinet Office.
[normal]Background [bold]&#xa0;[bold]4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Deregulation Bill is a cross-Government Cabinet Office-led Bill. It forms part of the government’s commitment to reduce the overall burden of regulation and to cut ‘red tape’ during this Parliament. The implementation of that programme includes measures given effect by administrative changes and secondary legislation. The Bill is one of a number 
[normal]of
[normal] government bills that is taking forward reforms where their implementation requires primary legislation. Its purpose is to change various pieces of legislation in 
[normal]order
[normal] to reduce or remove unnecessary legislative burdens on businesses, civil society, the taxpayer and individuals; and, additionally, to repeal some redundant legislation. 
[normal]5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Bill includes measures relating to general and specific areas of business, companies and insolvency, the use of land, housing, transport, communications, the environment, education and training, entertainment, public authorities and the administration of justice. It also provides for a duty on those exercising specified regulatory functions to have regard to the desirability of promoting economic growth. It repeals some legislation that is no longer of any practical use, and provides ministers with a power to make similar repeals in the future via secondary legislation. 
[normal]Provisions[bold] which confer [bold]delegated powers[bold] [bold]6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]provisions
[normal] in the Bill which confer these powers are identified below. The purpose of the delegated powers taken, and an explanation as to why the matter is to be left to delegated legislation and why the relevant department has chosen a particular procedure, are then set out in relation to each relevant clause.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Territorial coverage [bold]7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Any amendment of existing legislation has the same extent as the original legislation except where specified by clause 63(2) and (3). Clause 63(2) and (3) specify certain paragraphs in 
[normal]Schedule 16, which repeal
[normal] legislation which is no longer of practical use. 
[normal]8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]By virtue of clause 63(5), the new powers granted to a Minister of the Crown by clauses 49 (power to amend legislation to describe actual commencement dates), 51
[normal]-57
[normal] (power to 
[normal]disapply
[normal] legislation which is no longer of practical use) 
[normal]and 58-61
[normal] (provisions concerning the promotion of economic growth) form part of the law of England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. The provisions concerning consequential changes, commencement and short title set out in clauses 62, 64 and 65 also so apply, by virtue of the same clause. 
[normal]Devolution
[normal]9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Except where the contrary is expressly stated, the powers conferred by the Bill are not exercisable in a devolved area. 
[normal]Clause 1: [bold]Health and safety at work: general duty of self-employed persons[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The Secretary of State 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power exercisable by:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory i
[normal]nstrument 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parliamentary procedure:
[normal]              
[normal] Negative Resolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause provides the Secretary of State with a new regulation-making power under the Health and Safety at Work etc. Act 1974
[normal].
[normal]11.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 3(2) of the 1974 Act imposes a general duty on all self-employed persons to conduct their undertaking in such a way to ensure, so far as reasonably practicable, that they themselves and persons other than their employees who may be affected by it are not exposed to risks to their health and safety. 
[normal]12.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Clause 1 limits the scope of section 3(2) so that only those self-employed who conduct a “relevant undertaking” will continue to hold a duty under this provision.
[normal]13.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This 
[normal]new regulation-making 
[normal]power is exercisable in relation to England and Wales and Scotland. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Clause 1(3) defines “relevant undertaking” as an undertaking of a prescribed description, or any other undertaking that could expose other persons to risks to their health and safety. 
[normal]15.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]“Prescribed” has a specific meaning within the 1974 Act, defined in section 53(1) as prescribed by regulations made by the Secretary of State. Clause 1(3) therefore enables the Secretary of State to make regulations for the purpose of bringing the
[normal] self-employed within the scope of the section 3(2) duty. 
[normal]Unless a relevant undertaking has been prescribed, a self-employed person will only owe a duty to themselves if their undertaking poses a risk of harm to others.
[normal]16.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The regulation-making power in clause 1(3) affords the Secretary of State a degree of flexibility because a number of different 
[normal]descriptions  of
[normal] an  undertaking could be given in the regulations. For example, a “prescribed description” could be by reference to the activities that the undertaking engages in (e.g. construction
[normal]) ,
[normal] the hazardous substances it uses, or a combination of these things. 
[normal]17.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Secretary of State can exercise this power at his or her own discretion, or 
[normal]on  a
[normal] recommendation from the Health and Safety Executive who, by virtue of section 11(3) of the 1974 Act, may submit to the Secretary of State such proposals as it considers appropriate for the making of regulations. 
[normal]18.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Key stakeholders will be consulted and their responses taken into account prior to a relevant undertaking being prescribed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification 
[normal]of 
[normal] the
[normal] delegation
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]19.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The department considers it necessary for the Secretary of State to be given a separate regulation-making power to prescribe a relevant undertaking because 
[normal]it  will
[normal] give the assurance that those self-employed persons working in high hazard industries or engaging in  high hazard activities (who would be expected to pose the highest risks of harm to others, as well as themselves) will not be exempt from the general duty under section 3(2) of the 1974 Act. This approach will make it clear and unambiguous to those working in high risk industries that they will not be exempt from section 3(2), and that they will still have a duty to conduct their undertaking in such a way as to ensure that they and others are not exposed to risks to their health and safety. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]20.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]It is appropriate for relevant undertakings to be prescribed through secondary legislation because it is anticipated that the kind of undertaking that needs to be prescribed may be subject to change and require regular updating to reflect fluctuating or emerging risks associated with a variety of different workplace activities or sectors. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of Parliamentary scrutiny
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]21.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Regulations made under the power conferred by clause 1(3) will be subject to the negative resolution procedure.  Section 82(3)
[normal] of the 1974 Act 
[normal]provides that any power to make regulations conferred by Part 1 of the Act 
[normal]( which
[normal] includes section 3) shall be exercisable by statutory instrument and subject to annulment (subject to an exce
[normal]ption set out in section 82(4), 
[normal]which is not relevant here). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]22.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Statutory instruments made under this clause will not make amendments to primary legislation, therefore the additional procedural hurdles and increased occupation of Parliamentary time associated with the affirmative procedure is not considered appropriate. However
[normal],
[normal] these regulations will effectively bring individuals within the scope of the primary legislation. Accordingly, the department considers the negative resolution procedure provides the appropriate level of scrutiny for detailed and technical provisions regarding health and safety at work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 3 and [bold]Schedule[bold] 1: English apprenticeships: simplification – inserts [bold]sections[bold] [bold] A1[bold] to [bold]A7 into the Apprenticeships, Skills, Children and Learning Act 2009[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Section A1 (2) and A1 (4) and (5): Approved English apprenticeship
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The Secretary of State 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power exercisable by:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory i
[normal]nstrument 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parliamentary procedure:
[normal]              
[normal] Negative Resolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]23.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 
[normal]A1(
[normal]2) sets out the meaning of an approved English apprenticeship for the purposes of the new Chapter A1 of the 
[normal]Apprenticeships, Skills, Children and Learning Act 2009 (“the 2009 Act”). 
[normal]It is an arrangement which either takes place under an approved English apprenticeship agreement or is an alternative English apprenticeship and, in either case, satisfies any conditions specified in regulations made by the Secretary of State.  Section 
[normal]A1(
[normal]4) confers a power on the Secretary of State to describe the kind of arrangements which are alternative English apprenticeships for the purposes of the new Chapter. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]24.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The background is that Schedule
[normal] 1 inserts a new Chapter A1 in Part 1 of 
[normal]the 2009 Act. 
[normal]Chapter 1 currently provides a regime for both English apprenticeships and Welsh apprenticeships. The new Chapter 
[normal]A
[normal]1 relates only to English apprenticeships. The existing Chapter 1 will continue to apply to Welsh apprenticeships.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]25.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The new provisions follow a review of apprenticeships by Doug Richard in 2012. He recommended that the government improve the quality of apprenticeships and introduce more employer focus. Chapter A1 simplifies the existing system. It introduces new concepts of approved English apprenticeships and approved apprenticeship standards.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]26.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Secretary of State has power to make regulations requiring the apprenticeship and the apprenticeship agreement to satisfy specified conditions. The Secretary of State also has the power to issue certificates to those who complete an approved English apprenticeship. The provisions as a whole reduce bureaucratic burdens, for example by abolishing apprenticeship frameworks and the issuing authorities who issue them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]27.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]These 
[normal]new delegated 
[normal]powers are exercisable in
[normal] relation to
[normal] England only.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of new section 
[normal]A1(
[normal]2) 
[normal]28.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section A1(2) provides a power for the Secretary of State to specify conditions which must be satisfied in 
[normal]order
[normal] for an arrangement to be an approved English apprenticeship for the purposes of the new Chapter A1. The Department envisages that this power will be used to specify common requirements that all apprenticeships must meet.  These common requirements may change from time to time and therefore it would be inappropriate to specify them in primary legislation.  For example, the Secretary of State may wish to specify a minimum duration to allow all apprentices sufficient time to practise and embed the skills they have learned. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of new section 
[normal]A1(
[normal]4) &amp; (5)
[normal]29.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 
[normal]A1(
[normal]4) and (5) provide a power for the Secretary of State to describe the kinds of arrangements which constitute alternative
[normal] English apprenticeships.  The d
[normal]epartment envisages that the Secretary of State will use this power to describe arrangements which are suitable for apprenticeships, but where the arrangements cannot satisfy the employment requirements of an approved English apprenticeship agreement.  
[normal]Regulations made under a similar existing power at section 1(5) of the 2009 Act exist for certain occupations where the apprentice is part of a crew or collective in the fishing, creative or performance industries. Regulations also exist for elite athletes undertaking the Sporting Excellence Apprenticeship with the hope of competing in 
[normal]the
[normal] Commonwealth or Olympic Games.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation: new section 
[normal]A1(
[normal]2)
[normal]30.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The main elements of approved English apprenticeships – apprenticeship agreements, approved apprenticeship standards, and certificates are set out in the new sections. Following consultation with employers and other stakeholders, it is very likely that further detailed conditions will be identified as being ones that all apprenticeships should meet
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]f
[normal]or example a minimum duration, a minimum amount of off-the-job learning, or minimum levels of English and maths 
[normal]achievement t
[normal]hat need to be acquired to complete an apprenticeship.  These requirements may change from time to time, for example in response to changes in policy priorities, or as new English and maths qualifications become available or their titles change.  As such it would be inappropriate to specify them i
[normal]n primary legislation, and the d
[normal]epartment considers that the use of delegated powers to specify conditions that must apply to an approved English apprenticeship is appropriate.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation: new section 
[normal]A1(
[normal]4) and (5)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]31.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The power to describe the kind of arrangements which constitute alternative English apprenticeships is similar to the power currently contained in section 1(5) of the 2009 Act to specify alternative English completion conditions. It is envisaged that
[normal] the power will be used by the d
[normal]epartment for the same purpose. 
[normal]The department
[normal] is encouraging the use of more innovation within apprenticeships and a new apprenticeship standard can be developed at any time.  Delegation allows for the creation of an 
[normal]apprenticeship  in
[normal] exceptional circumstances, for example in certain circumstances where a person is self employed, or where a sector and individual could benefit from an approved apprenticeship.  Delegation will require detailed consideration of the merits of any application for an alternative English apprenticeship.  A
[normal] 
[normal]need to use primary legislation would inevitably lead to delay and difficulty in keeping up with developments, and might constrain flexibility within the system.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of p
[normal]arlia
[normal]mentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]32.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The department considers that the use of the negative procedure to specify conditions that must apply to an approved English 
[normal]a
[normal]pprenticeship is appropriate. Section 262(5) makes the current (and similar) regulation making power subject to the negative procedure.
[normal]33.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The d
[normal]epartment also considers the use of the negative procedure to describe the kinds of arrangements which constitute alternative English apprenticeships to be appropriate.  
[normal]34.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Regulations on alternative apprenticeships under the current law first came into effect in 2012 and were amended in 2013 using the affirmative procedure.  On both occasions only cases of genuine merit were proposed and on both occasions the 
[normal]R
[normal]egulations were approved unanimously and without controversy.  In 2013 three formal requests for alternative English completion conditions were received.  Of those only one was recommended for inclusion in the regulations and even this one was subject to considerable challenge before it went forward.  The department believes it has proved effective at weeding out cases that are not appropriate for apprenticeships. The sifting of requests has become largely an administrative act, and has not proved to be controversial or of wide interest.
[normal]35.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]As a result, the department does not consider that the additional cost, procedural hurdles and occupation of Parliamentary time associated with the affirmative procedure (which applies under the current law) are appropriat
[normal]e to these powers; a change to 
[normal]the 
[normal]negative  procedure
[normal] will enable the Secretary of State to act more swiftly where necessary to encourage innovation within apprenticeships and to respond to the nation’s needs at lower overall cost to the public purse. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]New section 
[normal]A1(
[normal]3)(c): Approved English apprenticeship agreements
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The Secretary of State 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power exercisable by:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory i
[normal]nstrument 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parliamentary procedure:
[normal]              
[normal] Negative Resolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]36.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section A1(3)(c) provides a power for the Secretary of State to specify conditions which must be satisfied in 
[normal]order
[normal] for an agreement to be regarded as an approved English apprenticeship agreement for the purposes of the new Chapter A1. 
[normal]37.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This power is exercisable in relation to England only.
[normal]The effect of the section
[normal]38.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The d
[normal]epartment envisages that the Secretary of State will use this power to prescribe the content of an apprenticeship agreement in a manner that minimises the burden and bureaucracy for employers
[normal] 
[normal]possibly by prescribing standard wording.
[normal]Justification of the Delegation 
[normal]39.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The power to specify conditions for approved English apprenticeship agreements is similar (but arguably wider than) the current power contained in section 32(2) of the 2009 Act to prescribe the form of an
[normal] apprenticeship agreement. The d
[normal]epartment envisages 
[normal]that it will be used for the same purposes, and considers that the use of delegated power to specify conditions remains appropriate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]40.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The department considers that the use of the negative procedure to specify conditions which must be satisfied in 
[normal]order
[normal] for an agreement to be regarded as an approved English apprenticeship agreement is appropriate. Section 262(5) of the 2009 Act subjects regulations made under section 32(2) of the 2009 Act to the negative procedure. Regulations were introduced in 2012 and were not controversial.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]New Section 
[normal]A7(
[normal]5): Crown Servants and Parliamentary Staff
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The Secretary of State 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power exercisable by:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory i
[normal]nstrument 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parliamentary procedure:
[normal]              
[normal] Negative Resolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]41.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section A7(5) provides a power for the Secretary of State to apply any provision  of Chapter 1 with modifications to apprenticeship agreements under which a person undertakes Crown employment, service as a member of the naval, military or air forces of the Crown, or 
[normal]employment 
[normal]as a relevant member of the House of Lords or House of Commons staff.
[normal]42.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This power is exercisable in relation to England only. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the section
[normal]43.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This power provides the flexibility to modify the ne
[normal]w provision made by Chapter A1 
[normal]in its application to Crown servants and parliamentary staff.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the Delegation
[normal]44.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This power is very similar to the power at section 36(5) of the 2009 Act which is currently subject to the negative procedure. 
[normal]Justification of the level of Parliamentary Scrutiny
[normal]45.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The d
[normal]epartment believes that the power will be used for essentially the same purposes as the current power at section 36(5) of the 2009 Act and therefore considers that the level of scrutiny should remain as at present.
[normal]New section A3: Apprenticeship Certificates
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The Secretary of State 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power exercisable by:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory i
[normal]nstrument 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parliamentary procedure:
[normal]              
[normal] Negative Resolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]46.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This section provides the Secretary of State with the power to make provision about applications for apprenticeship certificates, the supply of copies of apprenticeship certificates and the charging of fees for the issue of a certificate or supply of a copy.
[normal]47.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This power is exercisable in relation to England only. 
[normal]The effect of the section
[normal]48.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The d
[normal]epartment envisages that the Secretary of State will use these powers to replace certificates (for example if these have been lost by the individual), or 
[normal]to charge a fee for issuing and - or 
[normal]- 
[normal] replacing
[normal] certificates.  This will be beneficial to the individual as it will give them evidence of their apprenticeship and the achievement of their apprenticeship, which they will find helpful when, for example, seeking a new job.  
[normal]Justification of the Delegation
[normal]              
[normal]49.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]These powers replace the powers in sections 3 and 4 of the 2009 Act (so far as relating to English apprenticeships). The new sections as a whole will simplify the current system by removing the role of English certifying authorities. In future there may be situations where an apprenticeship certificate may not be required to be issued, for example where a trade specific certificate is the main recognisable standard for a particular occupation.  The use of the delegated power will regulate the supply of certificates and enable the Secretary of State to charge a fee for issuing or supplying a certificate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]50.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The supply of copy certificates and the charging of fees for this or for the issue of an apprenticeship certificate is largely an administrative task and the department considers that the use of the negative procedure is appropriate.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 4 and [bold]Schedule[bold] 2: Driving Instructors [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on:
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] 
[normal]Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parliamentary procedure:
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative resolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]51.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The amendments made by 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2 provide for a single system of registration for driving instructors which applies to both instructors who are disabled and those who are not. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]52.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Under the new system the Registrar of Approved Driving Instructors will have power to require a person, whether disabled or not, to undergo an assessment as to their ability to control a  vehicle in an emergency (“an emergency control assessment”) and to issue a certificate where satisfied of the person’s ability to do so (“an emergency control certificate”).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]53.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The new system requires changes to the regulation-making powers in Part 5 of the Road Traffic Act 1988. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]54.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Part 1 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2 amends Part 5 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 in the form it will be in once the amendments made to it by the Road Safety Act 2006 come into force.  Part 2 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2 amends Part 5 as it has effect before those amendments come into force.  
[normal]55.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]These powers are exercisable in 
[normal]relation to 
[normal]England and Wales and Scotland
[normal].
[normal]The effect of Part 1 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2
[normal]Paragraph 2(a) – amending section 124(3)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]56.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Under section 123 a person is prohibited from giving paid driving instruction of any prescribed
[normal] description unless registered in respect of that description. Regulations under section 124 may prescribe circumstances in which the section 123 prohibition does not apply. In particular, regulations may be made so that in prescribed 
[normal]circumstances persons who are training to be driving instructors are not required to be registered. Section 124(3) sets out particular circumstances which may be so prescribed. Paragraph 2(a) of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2 amends section 124 so as to make it clear that those circumstances could include the circumstance that a person holds a current emergency control certificate. This would allow regulations to be made to exempt trainee driving instructors from the requirement to register in circumstances where the trainee holds an emergency control certificate.
[normal]Paragraph 3(3) – amending section 125
[normal]57.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 125A of the 1988 Act is repealed by paragraph 5 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2. However, the definitions of “disability” and “relevant disability” given by section 
[normal]125A(
[normal]8) are still required for the purposes of Part 5 of the 1988 Act, as amended. Accordingly, paragraph 3(3) amends section 125 to reproduce the definitions. This has the effect of preserving the current power to prescribe by regulations a disability which is to be treated as a relevant disability for the purposes of the Part.   
[normal]Paragraph 4(2
[normal])(
[normal]b) – amending section 125ZA(2)
[normal]58.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Under section 125ZA(1) the Registrar must register a person in respect of a description of driving instruction if the person makes an application for registration and the Registrar is satisfied that the prescribed conditions are met. Section 125ZA
[normal] 
[normal](2) sets out what conditions may, in particular, be prescribed. Paragraph 4(2) amends section 125ZA so as to add conditions requiring a person who has been required to submit to an emergency control assessment to hold a current emergency control certificate. 
[normal]Paragraph 4(3
[normal])(
[normal]a) and (d) – amending section 125ZA(4)
[normal]59.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Under section 125ZA(3) a person may be registered in respect of a description of driving instruction subject to fulfilling prescribed conditions so long as the person continues to be registered. Section 
[normal]125ZA(
[normal]4) sets out what conditions may, in particular, be prescribed. Paragraph 4(3)(a) amends section 125ZA so as to add-
[normal]&#xad;
[normal](a) 
[normal]conditions
[normal] requiring a person to submit to an emergency control assessment (if required to do so by the Registrar in the circumstances mentioned in section 125(3D));
[normal](b) 
[normal]conditions
[normal] requiring a person to hold an emergency control certificate following such an assessment;
[normal](c), conditions requiring that, if instruction is to be given in circumstances where there is a reasonable expectation of an emergency arising which necessitates the instructor taking control of the vehicle, a person will only give such instruction if they would be able to take control of the vehicle if such an emergency arose.  
[normal]Paragraph 11(4) and (5) – amending section 
[normal]133A(
[normal]2) and (6) 
[normal]60.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 133A
[normal] 
[normal](2) sets out in full the meaning of “emergency control assessment”. It refers to an assessment of a person’s ability to take control of a vehicle of a class 
[normal]covered by the disabled person’s limited driving licence. This is no longer appropriate as, under the new system, people who are not disabled may also be required to undertake emergency control assessments. Paragraph 11(4) therefore amends section 
[normal]133A(
[normal]2) to refer instead to an assessment of a person’s ability to take control of a motor vehicle of a prescribed class. Paragraph 11(5) makes a consequential amendment to section 
[normal]133A(
[normal]6) which deal with the issue of emergency control certificates.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of Part 2 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2
[normal]Paragraph 17(2)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]61.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This paragraph inserts a new section 125(2C) and (2D) which sets out the circumstances in which the Registrar may require an applicant for registration to submit to an emergency control assessment. The circumstances are that the Registrar has reasonable grounds for believing that the applicant would be unable to take control of a motor car of a prescribed class if an emergency arose while he was giving driving instruction. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Paragraph 17(4) – amending section 125(5)
[normal]62.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Under section 125(5) continued 
[normal]registration
[normal] as an approved driving instructor is subject to the condition that the instructor will, upon request by the Registrar, submit to a test of continued ability and fitness to instruct. Paragraph 17(4) amends section 125(5) to add a further condition that the person will, if required to do so by the Registrar, submit to an emergency control assessment on a day within such period as may be prescribed.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Par
[normal]a
[normal]graph 17(7) – amending section 125
[normal]63.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This paragraph inserts section 125(8A) and (8B) which prevent a person making  a further application for registration if the person  has undergone an emergency control assessment, been refused an emergency control certificate and, in consequence,  either not been registered or had their name removed from the register. The person is  prevented from making a further application before the end of the period of 6 months , beginning with the date of the assessment, or before the end of such other period as may be prescribed, unless the Registrar is satisfied that there is good reason for allowing an earlier application.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Paragraph 17(9) – amending section 125(10)
[normal]64.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 125A of the 1988 Act is repealed by paragraph 18 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2. However, the definitions of “disability” and “relevant disability” given by section 
[normal]125A(
[normal]8) are still 
[normal]required for the purposes of Part 5 of the 1988 Act, as amended. Accordingly, paragraph 17(9) amends section 125 to reproduce the definitions. This has the effect of preserving the current power to prescribe by regulations a disability which is to be treated as a relevant disability for the purposes of the Part.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Paragraph 23(3) – amending section 129
[normal]65.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This paragraph inserts a new section 129(1B) and (1C) which set out the circumstances in which the Registrar may require a person who applies for a licence for the purpose of gaining experience in giving driving instruction to submit to an emergency control assessment. The circumstances are that the Registrar has reasonable grounds for believing that the applicant would be unable to take control of a motor car of a prescribed class if an emergency arose while he was giving driving instruction.
[normal]   
[normal]Paragraph 23(4) – amending section 129(2)
[normal]66.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In consequence of the new system, paragraph 23(4) substitutes a new section 129(2) to set out the circumstances in which the Registrar must grant a licence to persons seeking to gain experience in giving driving instruction. The amendment preserves the existing power to prescribe a fee for the granting of such a licence. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Paragraph 23(6) – amending section 129
[normal]67.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Under section 129(5) a licence granted for the purpose of enabling a person to gain experience in giving driving instruction may be granted subject to prescribed conditions. Paragraph 23(6) amends section 129 to provide that those conditions may include-
[normal](a) 
[normal]a
[normal] condition requiring the person granted the licence, if required to do so by the Registrar at a time when the circumstances in section 129(1C) apply, to submit to an emergency control assessment within a prescribed period;  
[normal](b) 
[normal]a
[normal] condition requiring that, if driving instruction is to be given in circumstances where there is a reasonable expectation of an emergency arising which necessitates the instructor taking control of the car, a person will only give such instruction if they  would be able to take control of the car if such an emergency arose. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Paragraph 25(4) 
[normal]and (5) – amending section 
[normal]133A
[normal](
[normal]2) and (6)
[normal]68.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 
[normal]133A(
[normal]2) sets out in full the meaning of “emergency control assessment”. It refers to an assessment of a person’s ability to take control of a motor car of a class covered by the disabled person’s limited driving licence. This is no longer appropriate as, under the new system, people who are not disabled may also be required to undertake emergency control assessments. Paragraph 25(4) therefore amends section 
[normal]133A(
[normal]2) to refer instead 
[normal]to an assessment of a person’s ability to take control of a motor car of a prescribed class. Paragraph 25(5) makes a consequential amendment to section 
[normal]133A(
[normal]6) which deals with the issue of emergency control certificates
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]69.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The amendments to Part 5 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 set out above expand the existing powers to make regulations in relation to driving instruction under that Part. The department continues to consider that the power to make such provision should be delegated to the Secretary of State as a regulation-making power. The detail of such provisions is more appropriate to secondary legislation. There is also likely to be a need to amend such provisions and make further provision from time to time which would be less conveniently achieved if contained in primary legislation.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny
[normal]70.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The negative resolution procedure applies, by virtue of section 195(3) of the Road Traffic Act 1988, to the existing powers to make regulations under Part 5 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 and the department continues to believe that this is appropriate. There should be Parliamentary scrutiny as the new powers extend to matters which are important to becoming and remaining a driving instructor but these are not so significant as to merit the affirmative procedure. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 7: [bold]Suppliers of fuel and fireplaces[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The Secretary of State 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power exercisable by: 
[normal]              
[normal]Publication of a list  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parliamentary procedure:
[normal]              
[normal] None
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]71.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Clause
[normal] 7 provides for the amendment of
[normal] Part 3, sections 20 and 21, of the Clean Air Act 1993 
[normal]which deals with 
[normal]Smoke Control Areas
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Under Part 3, it is an offence to emit smoke from the chimney of any building, or to emit smoke from a chimney (not being a chimney of a building) which serves the furnace of any fixed boiler or industrial plant, within a smoke control area unless using an authorised fuel or exempted appliance.  It is also an offence under section 23 to acquire or sell an unauthorised fuel within a smoke control area unless it is to be used under the specified requirements of an exempted appliance.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]72.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Currently the Secretary of State has the power under sections 20 and 21 of the Clean Air Act 1993 to authorise fuels by regulations and to exempt 
[normal]classes of fireplaces by 
[normal]order
[normal].  The regulations and 
[normal]order
[normal] are made by statutory instrument. They are made every six months (April and September) in England to coincide with the common commencement dates.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]73.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Authorised fuels and exempted fireplaces are not identified individually within the Clean Air Act 1993 but have been the subject of the power of delegated legislation as this allows new fuels and fireplaces to be authorised and exempted as they are developed. This Bill includes a modification to the
[normal] 
[normal]procedure by which thi
[normal]s delegated power is exercised.
[normal]74.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This change to the procedure applies in relation to
[normal] England only.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the change in delegation
[normal]75.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Manufacturers submit their products for testing to determine whether they are capable of being used without producing any smoke or a substantial quantity of smoke. The results are then checked by authorised contractors who subsequently make recommendations to the Secretary of State for inclusion in the six monthly 
[normal]SIs
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]76.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Under the Red Tape Challenge
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government made a commitment to simplify the process of exemption and authorisation, with a view to reducing burdens and improving efficiency.  Interested parties advised that the main burden associated with the current process was the delay between receiving a recommendation from authorised contractors and subsequent inclusion in the SIs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]77.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]To reduce the burden associated with the delay the Bill will amend sections 20 and 21 of the Clean Air Act to provide the Secretary of State with powers to authorise fuels and exempt appliances administratively by the publication of lists
[normal], thus avoiding 
[normal]the need for the production of the six monthly 
[normal]SIs
[normal].  The government intends that this power would be exercised by publishing lists on the gov.uk website. Initial lists of authorised fuels and exempt appliances would be published upon the commencement of this provision; these lists would include the products approved under the existing SIs to ensure that these do not lose their approved status. Thereafter updated versions of the lists would be published on a monthly basis as new products are approved.  This will allow manufacturers to bring their products to market more rapidly and allow consumers access to latest 
[normal]the 
[normal]technology.  The new procedure would enable lists to be updated and published as deemed necessary and if changes are required these will be made on a specific date each month.  The published lists will include details of the product type, conditions of use and date of grant, withdrawal
[normal] or variation of any approval.
[normal] Consumers without internet facilities may obtain access to the information via the 
[normal]Defra
[normal] Helpline
[normal] or by writing to or emailing the d
[normal]epartment direct.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification 
[normal]of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]78.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In 
[normal]order to qualify for
[normal] inclusion in the published lists, products must continue to meet the current requirements to demonstrate they are capable of being used without producing any smoke or a substantial quantity of smoke, therefore the safety and eligibility of these products for use in smoke control areas will remain unchanged. List publication and amendment will be subject to a robust system of quality controls and approval by senior staff.  The dates that products are added to the lists will be specified as will the dates of 
[normal]any  variations
[normal] or withdrawals of approvals. This will ensure that there is legal certainty with respect to which products may or may not be used, or, in the case of fuels, sold and acquired for use in a smoke control area at any given point in time.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]79.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The offences under sections 20 and 23 regarding the emission of smoke and the sale and acquisition of fuels for use within a smoke control area are not changed by the 
[normal]B
[normal]ill.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]80.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The authorisation or exemption of a product would only be withdrawn if evidence which demonstrates that the product does not meet the eligibility criteria for use in a smoke control area came to light. 
[normal]The department
[normal] is not aware of any appliance exemption being withdrawn to date.  Some authorised fuels have been removed in the past as manufacture had ceased and the fuel had not been available for many years.  Variations of authorisations and exemptions have previously consisted of changes to brand name or manufacturer’s name and the SIs have indicated any previously known names for clarity.  It is not intended to change this process.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]81.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In the event of evidence indicating that a product authorisation should be withdrawn 
[normal]the department
[normal] would liaise with interested parties first to investigate the validity of the evidence and then to ensure the withdrawal is publicised appropriately and where possible consumers are notified of the withdrawal.  The new centralised lists will highlight the date at which any withdrawals or amendments were made which is an improvement on the current system where it would be necessary to compare lengthy product lists in the SIs in 
[normal]order
[normal] for consumers and 
[normal]local authorities 
[normal]to identify any changes in the status of a product.  Finally there are some inherent additional legal safeguards to protect consumers and manufacturers.  The first of these is the requirement in the Clean Air Act 1993 to publish the lists.  The other is that a decision to withdraw an authorisation/exemption would be subject to judicial review if it is not taken correctly.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 9: Authorisation of insolvency practitioners[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Power conferred on:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Order made by statutory i
[normal]nstrument
[normal]Parliamentary procedure:
[normal]              
[normal]Negative
[normal] Resolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]82.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Clause 9 will amend Part 13 of the Insolvency Act 1986 to allow individuals to be authorised to act as an insolvency practitioner in relation to certain categories of appointment only.   Currently, individuals who are authorised to act as an insolvency practitioner are authorised in relation to all categories of appointment.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]83.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The amendments to Part 13 will provide for a person to be either fully authorised to act as an insolvency practitioner and practise in all categories of appointment or to be partially authorised to act only in relation to companies or only in relation to individuals.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]84.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The clause will also prevent partially authorised insolvency practitioners from acting in relation to a company or individual that is, or was, a member of a partnership that has outstanding liabilities, without permission from the court. Such appointments require an individual to be fully authorised because this type of insolvency requires knowledge of both company and individual insolvency law.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]85.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The new order-
[normal]making 
[normal] 
[normal]power
[normal] conferred as part of these changes is
[normal] exercisable in relation to England and Wales and Scotland
[normal].
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]86.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The clause will amend section 391 of the Insolvency Act 1986 relating to recognised professional bodies.  Section 391(1) and (2) will confer powers on the Secretary of State by 
[normal]order
[normal]:
[normal]In each case, an 
[normal]order
[normal] may be made only if it appears to the Secretary of State that the body regulates the practice of a profession and maintains and enforces rules for ensuring that its insolvency specialist members are fit and proper persons to act as insolvency practitioners and meet acceptable requirements as to education practical training and experience.   An 
[normal]order
[normal] which recognises a body for the purposes of granting partial authorisations has to state whether the partial authorisation relates to companies or to individuals.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]87.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 391(5) will require the Secretary of State by 
[normal]order
[normal] to revoke a professional body’s recognition where it appears that the body no longer meets the relevant requirements. The Secretary of State must also revoke recognition of a professional body in relation to full authorisations and replace it with recognition in relation to partial authorisations if
[normal] 
[normal]it appears to the Secretary of State that the body is capable of providing its insolvency specialist members with partial authorisation only.  The Secretary of State may in the relevant 
[normal]order
[normal] make transitional provisions to treat the body’s insolvency 
[normal]specialist members as fully or partially authorised, as the case may be, for a specified period after recognition is revoked, or revoked and replaced.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]88.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]An 
[normal]order
[normal] under section 391 must be made using the negative procedure by virtue of section 419 of the 1986 Act.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]89.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The powers to recognise professional bodies which may authorise their members to act as an insolvency practitioner and to revoke a body’s recognition in section 391 have been delegated since the Insolvency Act 1986 came into effect.  The clause will replace these powers with powers enabling the 
[normal]department
[normal] to recognise professional bodies in relation to full authorisation or in relation to partial authorisation.  Professional bodies which are currently recognised will be treated as bodies capable of providing full authorisations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]90.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The d
[normal]epartment considers that such powers should continue to be delegated to the Secretary of State.  Delegation will allow the 
[normal]department 
[normal]the flexibility to determine in any specific case whether or not a professional body meets or continues to meet the requirements for recognition and whether or not it is or continues to be capable of granting full authorisations or is capable of providing partial authorisations only.  It will enable the 
[normal]department
[normal] to take swift action pursuant to its determination.  A need to use primary legislation to address such issues would inevitably lead to delay and difficulty. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]91.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The d
[normal]epartment considers it appropriate that 
[normal]order
[normal]s relating to the recognition of professional bodies which regulate insolvency practitioners should continue to be made using the negative resolution procedure.  Decisions relating to the recognition of bodies which regulate insolvency practitioners can be taken by the executive to a large extent and do not
[normal] merit the additional level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny afforded by the affirmative procedure.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 10(3): New section 519A Companies Act 2006[bold]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Order
[normal] made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]92.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause inserts new section 519A into the Companies Act 2006 (“the Act”). Subsection (1) defines 
[normal]listed
[normal] company and, also, non-
[normal]listed
[normal] company, for the purposes of Part 16 (removal, resignation, etc of auditors). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]93.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]A 
[normal]listed
[normal] company is defined as a company whose “transferable securities” (these include shares and bonds) are included in the “official list” – in other words they have a main (London Stock Exchange) market listing – or whose shares are listed on a comparable market elsewhere in the EEA. A non-
[normal]listed
[normal] company is defined as a company that is not a 
[normal]listed
[normal] company.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]94.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In the context of auditors ceasing to hold office and the amendments to the Act being made by clause 10, there is a distinction between a 
[normal]listed
[normal] company and a non-
[normal]listed 
[normal]company and an enhanced framework of regulatory requirements applies in the case of the former. For instance, if an auditor of a 
[normal]listed
[normal] company is ceasing to hold office that auditor must in all cases send the company a statement of reasons as to why he or she is stepping down. If an auditor of a non-
[normal]listed
[normal] company is ceasing to hold office, however, that requirement does not apply in all cases – it applies where an auditor leaves before the end of his or her term and either one or more of the auditor’s reasons for leaving is of regulatory interest or there are matters which the auditor thinks the company’s shareholders or creditors should know about.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]95.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The sending of such a statement leads in turn to other obligations on the part of the auditor or the recipient – for instance, the company must (generally speaking) send a copy of such to a statement to its shareholders and creditors and to the Registrar of Companies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Devolution
[normal]96.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The new order-making
[normal] power
[normal] conferred by the 
[normal]clause 
[normal] is
[normal] exer
[normal]cisable in relation to 
[normal]England and Wales, 
[normal]Scotland and Northern Ireland
[normal]. In relation to 
[normal]Northern 
[normal]Ireland, this i
[normal]s a transferred area. Discussions with the devolved administration about seeking a legislative consent motion. 
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]97.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Subsection (5) of new section 519A provides that the Secretary of State may by 
[normal]order
[normal] amend the definition of 
[normal]listed
[normal] company. Since a non-
[normal]listed
[normal] company is simply defined as a company that is not a 
[normal]listed
[normal] company, amending the definition of 
[normal]listed
[normal] 
[normal]company
[normal] 
[normal] will
[normal] simultaneously have the effect of altering what is a non-
[normal]listed
[normal] company. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]98.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Amending the definition of 
[normal]listed
[normal] company may be a relatively trivial matter – markets may change over time and the power could, for instance, be used to update terms and references used in the then current definitions (the power may already have been used of course) that have become obsolete. The power could, however, be used to provide that certain types of company, in respect of which the enhanced framework does not apply, will thereupon be subject to that framework. An example would be amending the definition to include companies that are listed on secondary markets or which are currently unlisted but, because of their size or the sector in which they operate, are of 
[normal]considerable economic or public importance.  Conversely, the power could be used to amend the definition to exclude a type of company from the list of 
[normal]companies  in
[normal] respect of which the enhanced framework applies.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]99.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Subsection (6) of new section 519A provides that an 
[normal]order
[normal] pursuant to new subsection (5) is subject to the negative resolution procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]100.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Amending the definition of 
[normal]listed
[normal] compa
[normal]ny is justified because of the department
[normal]’s wish for flexibility as regards keeping the current (and any future) definitions up-to-date and as regards determining precisely what type of company will or will not be covered by the enhanced framework of auditor leaving statement requirements.     
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]101.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]On balance, and notwithstanding that this is a Henry VIII power, the department considers that the negative resolution procedure is appropriate. This is because, and as explained above, such a power might only be used in a very minor way – bringing references and terms used in the then current definitions up-to-date. Even if the power is used in a more material way, there will be cases in which there are no practical consequences. For instance, where the power is used to add new types of company (and thereby apply the enhanced framework to the same), the auditor of such a company may be sending the company a leaving statement in a case in which, prior to the exercise of the power, he would also have had to have sent such a statement – i.e. because he or she was leaving prior to the end of his or her term and, for example, there were matters which he or she thought the company’s shareholders needed to know about.  Moreover, these are technical, regulatory matters such that in any event the use of the power is not expected to attract widespread interest or be controversial. In th
[normal]e circumstances, the d
[normal]epartment does not consider that the a
[normal]dditional procedures and p
[normal]arliamentary engagement associated with an affirmative resolution procedure statutory instrument can be justified. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]102.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There are a number of existing Henry VIII powers on the face of the Act in respect of which the negative resolution procedure applies and which might therefore be considered a precedent. Section 857(1) is a power to make regulations further providing for the contents of a company’s annual return and subsection (2) provides that these regulations may amend the existing provisions at sections 855 and 856. Section 1099(4) relates to the Registrar of Companies obligations to keep an index of the names of companies and other bodies and allows the Secretary of State by 
[normal]order
[normal] to amend the list of other bodies at section 1099(3). Section 1160(1) is a power to make regulations amending the definitions of “subsidiary”, “holding company” or “wholly-owned subsidiary” – see section 1159 of and 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 6 to the Act. Note that, like the proposed power to amend the definition of “public interest 
[normal]company
[normal]”, each of these powers may be used in material way - making bodies or other persons subject to new obligations or, conversely, 
[normal]removing obligations to which bodies or other persons are subject.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]103.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Please note that the department
[normal] is considering whether it would be preferable to replace the terms ‘listed company’ and ‘non-listed company’
[normal] with alternative labels before the Bill is introduced in Parliament. 
[normal]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clauses 13 – 17; and clause 18, which introduces [bold]Schedule[bold] 6 [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]General introduction to the ‘rights of way’
[normal] provisions
[normal]104.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]By way of general background to these measures, Part 3 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (“the 1981 Act”) requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area. The local authorities concerned are referred to in that Act as “surveying authorities” and the maps and statements are referred to as “definitive maps and statements”. Part 3 also sets out the procedures which apply where an authority wishes to make a change to the definitive map and statement for its area or where someone applies for such a change to be made.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]105.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A definitive map and statement is conclusive evidence of certain matters. For example, if a map shows a footpath, this is generally conclusive evidence that the public had a right of way on foot over the land on a particular date.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]106.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Some rights of way are not recorded on a definitive map and statement. Section 53 of the Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000 (“the 2000 Act”). 
[normal]provides
[normal] for unrecorded rights of way created before 1949 to be extinguished immediately after 1 January 2026 (known as the “cut-off date”), subject to certain exceptions. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]107.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 2000 Act also confers power on the Secretary of State to, by regulations, make transitional provisions and savings, in particular for cases where (a) orders modifying definitive maps and statements have been made but not confirmed before the cut-off date; (b) applications for definitive map orders have been submitted before the cut-off date; or (c) orders have been quashed because of a legal error (section 56(2
[normal])(
[normal]b)).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]108.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Highways Act 1980 (“the 1980 Act”) also deals with public rights of way. For example, it allows applications to be made, in certain circumstances, to extinguish or divert a public right of way.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]109.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The new delegated powers conferred by the rights of way provisions in the Bill 
[normal]are  exercisable
[normal] in relation to England only. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 13: Unrecorded rights of way: protection from extinguishment[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory instrument. 
[normal](Extension of existing regulation making power.)
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]110.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause provides the Secretary of State with a method to protect certain public rights of way from extinguishment in 2026. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]111.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The general background to this, as explained in the general introduction to 
[normal]the rights of way provisions
[normal], is that Part 3 of the 1981 Act requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]112.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Some rights of way are not recorded on a definitive map and statement. Section 53 of the 2000 Act provides for the extinguishment, immediately after cut-off date, of unrecorded rights of way created before 1949, subject to certain limited exceptions. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]113.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]That Act also confers power on the Secretary of State to, by regulations, make transitional provisions and savings (see the general introduction to 
[normal]the rights of way provisions for further details of this.) 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]114.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is thought that, in the period immediately before the cut-off date, there will be a large volume of applications to surveying authorities for modifications to be made to the definitive map and statement to show rights of way that are currently unrecorded. This is because individuals and groups in the voluntary sector are likely to carry out research so that they can make applications to have unrecorded rights of way shown on a definitive map and statement (with the result that they will not be automatically extinguished after that date). There is concern that surveying authorities will also carry out research into unrecorded rights of way during this period in order to comply with the requirement that they keep under review definitive maps and statements. This could lead to surveying authorities unnecessarily duplicating the work of individuals and the voluntary sector.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]115.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The clause therefore inserts a new section 56A in the 2000 Act. This extends the regulation-making power in section 56(2) of that 
[normal]Act  to
[normal] enable the Secretary of State to make regulations enabling a surveying authority to designate, during a period of one year after the cut-off date, public rights of way extinguished immediately after that date under section 53 of that Act. The exercise of the power is subject to the negative resolution procedure (see section 56(6) of that Act).  The new section 56A also sets out what else may be included in the regulations. It is envisaged that the power to make regulations will be used to provide for designated rights to cease to be regarded as extinguished as from the time of designation. Where a right is designated, surveying authorities will be required to decide whether to modify the definitive map and statement to show the right of way. If a right of way is then sho
[normal]wn on the map, it will remain non-
[normal]extinguished. If the authority decides not to show the right of way, it will normally be extinguished again. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]116.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Provision may also be made as to the procedure applicable in relation to such a determination. The provision that may be made by virtue of subsection (1
[normal])(
[normal]d) includes provision applying 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 15 to the 1981 Act, subject to such modifications as may be specified in the regulations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]117.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Clause 13 is in the nature of a transitional or savings provisi
[normal]on. It is about 
[normal]the  transition
[normal] 
[normal]to a position where certain unrecorded public rights of way will no longer be able to be added to definitive maps and statements. It also provides a method to save unrecorded rights that would otherwise be extinguished on the cut-off date. It enables surveying authorities to wait until after the cut-off date to assess what research has been carried out by individuals and voluntary organisations. There will be a one-year period after that date within which they can act under the regulations to prevent rights of way being permanently extinguished. They will therefore be able to avoid duplicating any work done by individuals and voluntary organisations and focus, during the one-year period following the cut-off date, on areas where research has not been carried out by individuals and voluntary organisations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]118.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As explained above in the description of the effect of clause 13, the clause is in the nature of a transitional or savings provision. As explained in the general introduction to 
[normal]the rights of way provisions
[normal], the 2000 Act already confers power on the Secretary of State to, by 
[normal]regulations,
[normal] make transitional provisions and savings in relation to the cut-off date. 
[normal]The department
[normal] therefore considers it appropriate that further provision for 
[normal]transition and savings is also 
[normal]dealt with by delegated legislation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]119.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The department
[normal] also considers it appropriate that the procedure for the determination in relation to a designated public right of way be dealt with by delegated legislation. Clause 13 provides that the provision that may be made by virtue of subsection (1
[normal])(
[normal]d) includes provision applying 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 15 to the 1981 Act, subject to such modifications as may be specified in the regulations. 
[normal]The department’s
[normal] intention is to introduce a procedure that closely follows the procedure set out in 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 15. However, due to the 
[normal]fact that the procedure will apply for only a transitory period, and deal with designated public rights of way (and not rights of way generally), it is anticipated that various modifications of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 15 will be required. 
[normal]The department
[normal] has not finalised the details of the modified procedure, and needs the flexibility afforded by the regulation-making power.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justificat
[normal]ion of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]120.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As described above in the description of the effect of the clause, the exercise of the power is subject to the negative resolution procedure. Clause 13 sets out in some detail the matters which may be provided for in the transitory period during which public rights of way may be designated. 
[normal]The department 
[normal]considers in view of this that the negative resolution procedure is appropriate and proportionate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]121.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 56(2) of the 2000 Act also provides a precedent for transitional and savings provision relating to the cut-off date being subject to negative resolution procedure. 
[normal]The department 
[normal]does not see any good reason to depart from that in this case. One consequence of applying a different level of scrutiny in this case would be that provision for transition and savings would be fragmented, which
[normal] the department
[normal] considers a disadvantage for users.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 15: Applications by owners etc for public path orders[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]122.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause provides the Secretary of State with a method to extend the circumstances in which applications to extinguish or divert certain public rights of way may be made.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]123.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The background to this clause, as explained in the general introduction to 
[normal]the rights of way provisions, is that
[normal] the 1980 Act also deals with public rights of way. For example, it allows applications to be made, in certain circumstances, to extinguish or divert a public right of way.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]124.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Under section 118ZA of the 1980 Act, owners, lessees and occupiers of land used for agriculture, forestry or the breeding of keeping of horses may apply to a local authority for an order (“a public path extinguishment order”) which extinguishes a public 
[normal]right of way over a footpath or bridleway crossing the land.  Section 119ZA of that Act confers a comparable right to apply for an order to divert such a right of way (“a public path diversion order”).  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]125.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Under the current law, applications for a public path extinguishment order or a public path diversion order cannot be made in relation to other land, even where there would be good reasons for making such an order. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]126.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Further background to this clause is that under section 121D applicants for public path extinguishment orders or public path diversion orders have a right of appeal to the Secretary of State, in certain circumstances.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The e
[normal]ffect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]127.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Subsections (2) and (3) of the clause therefore amend, respectively, sections 118ZA(1) and 119ZA(1) of the 1980 Act to allow the Secretary of State to prescribe in regulations other kinds of land in England in respect of which such applications may be made. The effect of section 325(2) of that Act is that the exercise of the power is subject to the negative resolution procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]128.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As explained above in the introduction to this clause, applicants for public path extinguishment orders or public path diversion orders have a right of appeal to the Secretary of State, in certain circumstances. The Secretary of State has only limited powers to recover the costs of these kinds of appeals and thus is forced to bear some of the costs. Extending the circumstances in which applications may be made is therefore likely to have a bearing on public finances. 
[normal]The department 
[normal]needs the flexibility afforded by the delegated legislative power.
[normal] The 
[normal]department 
[normal] intends
[normal] to consider extending the circumstances in which applications may be made on an incremental basis, with coverage of the provisions being extended in light of the actual take up of the right of appeal and the impact on public finances.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]129.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As explained above in the description of the effect of the clause, the exercise of this power is subject to the negative resolution procedure.  As described above, subsections 
[normal](2) and (3) of the clause amend
[normal] the 1980 Act to allow the Secretary of State to prescribe in regulations certain kinds of land in England in respect of which applications for public path extinguishment or diversion orders may be made. 
[normal]The department
[normal] considers this is important, but not so important as
[normal] to require a higher degree of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny than that offered by the negative resolution procedure. 
[normal]The department 
[normal]therefore considers the negative resolution procedure to be appropriate and proportionate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 17: Applications for certain orders under Highways Act 1980: cost recovery[bold]Power conferred on:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]R
[normal]egulations made by statutory instrument. 
[normal](Extension of existing
[normal] 
[normal]regulation making power.)
[normal]Parliamentary
[normal] procedure: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Affirmative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction 
[normal]130.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause provides the Secretary of State with a method to enable local authorities to fix charges for certain orders under the 
[normal]Highways Act 
[normal]1980 Act locally. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]131.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]The background to this clause is that sections 118ZA and 119ZA of the 
[normal]Highways Act 1980
[normal] allow owners, lessees or occupiers of certain land to apply to local authorities for public path extinguishment orders or public path diversion orders. The amendments made by this clause deal with the recovery of costs in respect of such applications.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]132.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]Currently, the sections contain powers which allow the Secretary of State, in relation to England, or the Welsh Ministers, in relation to Wales, to prescribe charges payable on the making of such applications (and further charges where an order is made on the application). Under such regulations, the authority dealing with the application would be able to recover its costs but only up to the prescribed amount which would be set centrally and may not be at a level which would allow the authority to recover all of its costs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]133.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]The Secretary of State has a general power in section 150 of the Local Government and Housing Act 1989 (“1989 Act”) to allow authorities to allow local authorities to charge for certain things locally. The power is exercised by delegated legislation. However, this power is only available where there is no other power or duty to impose a charge.
[normal]The e
[normal]ffect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]134.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The clause therefore amends sections 118ZA and 119ZA of the
[normal] Highways Act
[normal] 1980 so as to limit the application of the charging provisions within those sections to Wales. The effect of this is to allow the Secretary of State (in relation to England) to use the power under section 150 of the 1989 Act to authorise charges to be imposed in respect of applications under sections 118ZA and 119ZA. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]135.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The power in section 150 of the 1989 Act is exercisable by delegated legislation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]The clause has the effect of allowing the delegated power in section 150 of the Local Government and Housing Act 1989 to be exercised in circumstances where it couldn
[normal]’t currently be exercised. The department
[normal] therefore considers that clause 17 should be justified.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]136.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 150 provides a precedent for the delegation of legislative powers to the Secretary of State to allow local authorities to 
[normal]charge for certain things. The department
[normal] considers it appropriate that this precedent is followed in respect of charges for certain orders under the Highways Act
[normal] 1980.
[normal]Justification of the level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny
[normal]137.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The department
[normal] considers it appropriate that the power in section 150 of the 1989 
[normal]Act ,
[normal] as extended by the clause, continues to be  subject to the affirmative resolution procedure. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Clause 18 and [bold]Schedule[bold] 6 paragraph 3: Modifications arising from administrative errors[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Introduction
[normal]138.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This provision provides the Secretary of State with power to introduce a modified procedure for the correction of administrative errors in maps and statements of public rights of way.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]139.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The background to this, as explained in the general introduction to 
[normal]the rights of way provisions
[normal], is that Part 3 of the 1981 Act requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]140.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Schedule
[normal]s 14 and 15 to the1981 Act set out the procedure which applies where an authority wishes to make a change to the definitive map and statement for its area or where someone applies for such a change to be made. There is provision for such things as the making of applications, the making of orders, notification, publicity, consultation, referral (of opposed orders), determination, and finally, confirmation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]141.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Administrative errors, such as a reference accompanying a path on a map to “FP23” when the path is in fact “FP33”, are often found in definitive maps and statements. There is currently not any separate procedure to deal with such cases. Surveying authorities are expected to follow the procedure in 
[normal]Schedule
[normal]s 14 and 15 to the 1981 Act. This is unnecessarily burdensome in cases where errors are obvious and very unlikely to be contentious. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The e
[normal]ffect of the
[normal] provision
[normal]142.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The provision therefore inserts a new section 53ZA in the 1981 Act. Under this provision the Secretary of State may introduce a modified procedure for the correction of administrative errors. The procedure must follow the existing procedure in 
[normal]Schedule
[normal]s 14 and 15 with such modifications as are prescribed in regulations. Subsection (3) provides that the exercise of this power is subject to negative resolution procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]143.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Subsection (1
[normal])(
[normal]a) to (c) specifies the circumstances where surveying authorities may use the new procedure. Firstly, authorities must be satisfied that an event of the kind specified in section 53(3
[normal])(
[normal]c) of the 1981 Act must have occurred (these are known as “evidentiary events”). An evidentiary event includes such things as the discovery by an authority that a public right of way shown on the definitive map of a particular description ought to be shown as a way of a different description.  Secondly, they must be satisfied that the need for the modification has arisen because of an administrative error. Thirdly, they must be satisfied that both the error and the modification needed to correct it are obvious. Surveying authorities must have regard to any guidance given by the Secretary of State in judging whether subsection (1
[normal])(
[normal]a) to (c) has been met.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]144.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The purpose of the provision is to provide a method to introduce a shorter procedure for correcting administrative errors in definitive maps and statements.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]145.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The department
[normal] envisages that the modified procedure will generally be same as the procedure in 
[normal]Schedule
[normal]s 14 and 15 to the 1981 Act, with modifications to make it shorter and more appropriate given the subject matter of administrative errors. The existing procedure relating to changes to definitive maps and statements is prescribed in primary legislation. 
[normal]The department
[normal] considers that the correction of administrative errors is important, but not so important as to require that the procedure for correcting administrative erro
[normal]rs be subject to the degree of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny associated with primary legislation. As explained above in the description of the effect of the provision, the clause sets out in detail the circumstances in which surveying authorities may use the modified procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]146.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The department
[normal] needs the flexibility afforded by a delegated legislative power. This will enable 
[normal]the department 
[normal]to change procedure relatively quickly, in view of practical experience and changes in case law.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]147.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As explained above in the description of the effect of the clause, the exercise of the power is subject to negative resolution procedure. As explained above the power to introduce a modified procedure is limited to relatively minor issues (administrative errors). 
[normal]The department 
[normal]considers therefore that the negative resolution procedure is appropriate and proportionate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 18 and [bold]Schedule[bold] 6 paragraph 4: Register of applications under section 53[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations 
[normal]made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]148.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This provision provides the Secretary of State with a method to specify that the duty to keep a register of applications under Part 3 of the 1981 Act does not apply to certain applications.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]149.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As described above in the general introduction, Part 3 of that Act requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review definitive maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area. Part 3 also sets out the procedures which apply where someone applies to a surveying authority for a change to be made to a definitive map and statement. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]150.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 
[normal]53B(
[normal]1) of that Act requires surveying authorities to keep a register of applications. Section 53B(6) provides that where section 53B mentions “prescribed” this means prescribed by the Secretary of State by regulations subject to the negative resolution procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]151.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Paragraph 6(4) inserts a new subsection (4A) into section 53B of the 1981 Act. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the provision
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]152.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The new provision states that regulations may provide that section 53B(1) does not apply with respect to applications made in England, or to any prescribed description of such applications, unless the authority serve notice under paragraph 1A(4)(b) of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 14 in relation to such an application. The effect of this is to confer a new delegated legislative power on the Secretary of State.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]153.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Paragraph 1A(4)(b) refers to notice being given of an authority’s decision to determine an application having concluded under paragraph 1A that there is a reasonable basis for the applicant’s belief that the definitive map and statement should be changed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the d
[normal]elegation
[normal]154.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The department’s
[normal] policy is that the duty to register applications generally should not apply with respect to applications made in England, unless the authority has served notice as described above. However, 
[normal]the department
[normal] is still considering whether it might wish to make exceptions to this general policy in respect of certain categories of application. 
[normal]The department
[normal] therefore needs the flexibility afforded by the delegation of legislative power. Section 53B(1) and (6) also provides a precedent for conferring delegated power on the Secretary of State to prescribe the information that might be contained in the register in regulations. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary scrutiny
[normal]155.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 
[normal]53B(
[normal]6) provides a precedent for regulations subject to the negative resolution procedure for prescribing the information that must be kept in the register. Whilst the exclusion of information from the register of all applications for changes to definitive maps and statements is an important matter, 
[normal]the department 
[normal]does not consider it so important that the affirmative resolution procedure ought to apply. There is very little public interest in applications for changes to definitive maps and statements where there is no reasonable basis for such changes to be made. However, the private landowner over whose land the alleged right subsists, may have some, albeit mild interest in an application notwithstanding that there is no reasonable basis for it. 
[normal]The department
[normal] therefor
[normal]e considers that some level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny is merited and that the negative resolution procedure is appropriate and proportionate. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 18 and [bold]Schedule[bold] 6 paragraph 5: Modifications of definitive map by consent: England[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on: 
[normal]              
[normal]Surveying authorities
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Order
[normal] 
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]None
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]156.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This provision provides the Secretary of State with power to introduce a shorter procedure for changes to definitive maps and statements of public rights of way where landowners give their consent.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]157.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]By way of background, as explained in the general introduction to 
[normal]the rights of way provisions
[normal], Part 3 of the 1981 Act requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area.
[normal] The local authorities concerned are referred to in that Act as “surveying authorities” and the maps and statements are referred to as “definitive maps and statements”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]158.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Part 3 also sets out the procedures which apply where an authority wishes to make a change to the definitive map and statement for its area or where someone applies for such a change to be made.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]159.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]Highways Act 
[normal]1980 also deals with public rights of way. For example, it allows applications to be made, in certain circumstances, to extinguish or divert a public right of way.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]160.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Unrecorded rights of way created before 1949 are sometimes discovered by surveying authorities. In such cases landowners might not object to the addition of the rights to definitive maps and statements if the right of way in question is reasonably diverted, to allow for current land usage. However, there is currently no provision for surveying authorities to modify definitive maps and statements and divert the right under the same procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect
[normal] of the provision
[normal]161.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The provision therefore inserts two new sections into the 1981 Act: sections 54B and 54C. The new section 54B sets out a new procedure by which an authority may by order modify the definitive map in consequence of certain kinds of application under section 53(5) of the Act. The new procedure is generally only available in respect of applications where evidence relates only to the existence of a right of way before 1949.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]162.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]One of the features of the new 
[normal]procedure,
[normal] is that a landowner over whose land an alleged public right of way subsists must consent to it being used. The authority may make 
[normal]a ”
[normal]diversion order”, under section 54B(2)(a) in order to secure this consent. This may divert the public right of way in question. Section 
[normal]54B(
[normal]3) provides that the effect of a diversion order is twofold. It will create a new public path, and extinguish the public right over so much of the existing path as is necessary to enable the diversion.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]163.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The department considers that the delegation is arguably a delegation of legislative power, and that the provision should be justified in this memorandum. As explained above under the description of the effect of the provision, a diversion order will have the effect of creating a new public path, and extinguishing the public right over so much of the existing path as is necessary to enable the diversion . As such, an order will affect the rights of the general public over the public over a public right of way being diverted.  A diversion order is therefore arguably 
[normal]legislative
[normal] in character as a “creation and promulgation of a general rule of conduct without reference to particular cases”.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]164.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The provision confers power to make modification consent orders including special orders on surveying authorities. It is intended to give surveying authorities (which are generally local authorities) more scope to resolve disputes about the existence of public rights of way at a local level. The provision sets out the limits to the exercise of the power (for instance that the authority must obtain the consent of all landowners). There is also a precedent for the function of diverting rights of way to be delegated to local decision-makers (see section 119 of the 1980 Act which confers power on councils to by order divert certain
[normal] kinds of public rights of way).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of Parliamentary Scrutiny
[normal]165.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The delegated power in this instance is exercised by order with no parliamentary scrutiny. 
[normal]The department 
[normal]considers this to be appropriate as the power is delegated to local authorities. There is also a precedent for this. Orders diverting rights of way under section 119 of the 1980 Act are not generally subject to parliamentary scrutiny.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 18 and [bold]Schedule 6 paragraphs 6(4), 6(8) and 6(11): Ascertainment of rights of way: Part 1 – Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981: [bold]powers to prescribe forms[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations
[normal] made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]166.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]These provisions provide the Secretary of State with a method for prescribing the form of various documents associated with the procedure for ascertaining public rights of way in England.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]167.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As described above in the general 
[normal]to the rights of way provisions
[normal], Part 3 of the 1981 Act requires local authorities in England and Wales to maintain and keep under review maps and statements showing public rights of way in their area. Part 3 introduces Schedule 14 to that Act which sets out the procedures which apply where an authority wishes to make a change to the definitive map and statement for its area or where someone applies for such a change to be made.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]168.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Various provisions in Schedule 14 delegate power to “prescribe” something. Paragraph 5 of Schedule 14 states that this power is exercisable by the Secretary of State by regulations subject to the negative resolution procedure. 
[normal]For example, 
[normal]paragraph 1 of Schedule 14 provides that an “application shall be submitted in the prescribed form”. In this example paragraph 1 confers delegated power on the Secretary of State to prescribe the form of applications made under paragraph 1 in regulations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]169.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Paragraphs 6(4), 6(8) and 6(11)
[normal] of Schedule 6 to the 
[normal]Bill make various amendments to the existing procedure:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The e
[normal]ffect of the provisions
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]170.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The effect of each of these new provisions is that where they refer to doing something “in the prescribed form” they confer a new delegated power. The power is, by virtue of paragraph 5 of Schedule 14 conferred on the Secretary of State and is exercisable by regulations pursuant to the negative resol
[normal]ution
[normal] procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification for delegation
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]171.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is precedent in Schedule 14 to the 1981 Act for the Secretary of State to prescribe in regulations the form of various notices and forms associated with the procedure for public rights of way in England (
[normal]eg
[normal] paragraph 1 to Schedule 14:see 
[normal]paragraph 168 
[normal] above). 
[normal]The department
[normal] considers it appropriate that the precedent is followed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of level of parliamentary scrutiny
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]172.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The exercise of the existing delegated powers to prescribe certain things in Schedule 14 are subject to negative resolution procedure (
[normal]eg
[normal] paragraph 1 to Schedule 14
[normal]:see
[normal] 
[normal]paragraph 168
[normal] above). 
[normal]The department
[normal] considers it appropriate that this precedent is followed
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 22 and [bold]Schedule[bold] 7[bold] paragraph 8[bold]: removal of restrictions on provision of passenger rail services [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Order made by statutory i
[normal]nstrument (extension of existing 
[normal]order
[normal]-making procedure)
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]173.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This paragraph widens the scope of the conditions and other provisions which the Secretary of State may include in any 
[normal]order
[normal] he makes under section 24 
[normal]of the 
[normal]Railways Act 1993 (“the 1993 Act”) (i.e. an 
[normal]order
[normal] exempting passenger rail services from the franchising regime of sections 23 to 31 of that Act). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]174.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Most main line passenger rail services in England and Wales are designated under section 23(1) of the 1993 Act as services to be provided under franchise agreements with the Secretary of State
[normal]. These franchised services are provided by private rail operating companies under franchise agreements made with the Secretary of State under section 29. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]175.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Because, under the 1993 Act, the Secretary of State is the sole main line passenger rail franchising authority for England and Wales, other persons cannot directly procure themselves main line rail services which have been designated for franchising. However the Secretary of State may, by 
[normal]order
[normal] under section 24 of the 1993 Act, exempt services from designation and thus carve them out of the franchising system. This would enable others to provide main line r
[normal]ail services 
[normal]instead of the Secretary of State. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]176.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is envisaged that the section 24 
[normal]order
[normal] making power would be used, in conjunction with clause 22 of the Bill, to enable Passenger Transport Executives to take over the provision of regional passenger rail services from central government.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]177.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]These powers are exercisable 
[normal]in relation to rail services in En
[normal]gland and Wales, and in Scotland other than
[normal] for rail services which start and end in Scotland. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of 
[normal]Schedule 7 paragraph 8
[normal] 
[normal]178.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The effect of the paragraph is to insert a new section 24A into the 1993 Act which would expand the scope of conditions and provisions which the Secretary of State may include in a section 24 
[normal]order
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]179.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 24A would enable the Secretary of State to apply similar railway asset protection, contract enforcement and asset transfer provisions in connection with an “operator agreement” (i.e. a contract for de-designated passenger rail services) as currently apply in connection with franchise agreements of the Secretary of State. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]180.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]More specifically section 24A would enable a section 24 de-designation 
[normal]order
[normal] of the Secretary of State to: -
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]181.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 7 
[normal]paragraph
[normal] 8 only affects section 24 Railways Act 1993 de-designation 
[normal]order
[normal]s made by the Secretary of State (i.e. 
[normal]order
[normal]s which relate to passenger rail services other than ones which start and end in Scotland). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]182.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The new section 24A of the 1993 Act would enable the Secretary of State, in carving out passenger rail services from the franchising system, to apply equivalent railway asset protection, contract enforcement and asset transfer provisions as would have continued to apply had they remained within the franchising regime. In that sense the Secretary of State would be able to maintain substantial continuity in the legal framework which applied.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]183.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] These railway asset protection provisions would ensure that assets needed for railway operations were kept intact, such that upon operator default or failure the railway operations could be taken over as a going concern by a successor, thus enabling continuity of passenger rail services.    
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]184.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] The contract enforcement provisions would strengthen the ability of the procurement body to be able to secure compliance with the terms of the passenger services contract b
[normal]y 
[normal]providing a statutory enforcement system to complement the normal civil law enforcement processes. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]185.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The asset transfer provisions would enable a more effective and efficient transfer of railway assets from an outgoing operator to a successor upon contract expiry or early termination.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]186.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] The 
[normal]department
[normal] envisages decentralisation of regional passenger rail services involving regional franchise operations being taken over by Passenger Transport Executives. This has led to a fresh look at relevant legislation to ensure any decentralisation could be made to work effectively. It seems logical in this context to enable de-designated regional passenger rail to be able to be underpinned by equivalent legal provisions to those that apply to franchised services. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]187.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] The d
[normal]epartment considers it is appropriate for these issues to be addressed in secondary legislation because this would allow the Secretary of State to determine in any specific case, and within the scope of the powers, what provision should be made to apply. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Justification of the level of p
[normal]arliamentary
[normal] s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]188.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The power under section 24 of the 1993 Act to make an 
[normal]order
[normal] is exercisable by statutory instrument subject to negative
[normal] resolution
[normal]. A section 24 
[normal]order
[normal] is only made where the railway services in question are already subject to the franchise regime. The extended scope of the power would enable similar provisions to apply after franchise de-designation as already applied before de-designation. Any operator contracted to provide passenger rail services by a party in whose favour a section 24 
[normal]order
[normal] is made would be engaged by entry into a freely negotiated commercial contract in the knowledge that su
[normal]ch provisions would apply. The d
[normal]epartment therefore considers that the extended scope to such 
[normal]order
[normal]s, enabled by 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 7 paragraph 8 of the Bill, is not such as to m
[normal]erit application of additional p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny through the affirmative procedure. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 23(a)[bold] and Schedule 8, Part 1:[bold] Permit Schemes: Removal of requirement for Secretary of State [bold]approval[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on: 
[normal]              
[normal]The relevant local authority 
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Local authority 
[normal]order
[normal] 
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]N
[normal]one
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]189.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Permit schemes are designed to control the carrying out of specified works in the area covered by the scheme. Permit schemes cover both street works and works carried out by the local highway authority. A permit must be sought from the relevant local authority for works which are to be carried out in a street covered by a permit scheme. Currently, permit schemes prepared by local highway authorities in England must, before they are implemented, be submitted to the Secretary of State for approval and given effect to by an 
[normal]order
[normal] made by the Secretary of State. This clause removes the requirement that the Secretary of State must approve and give effect to a permit scheme by 
[normal]order
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]190.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Part 3 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 provides for permit schemes. Section 34 concerns the implementation of local highway authority permit schemes. Section 34(2) provides 
[normal](in relation to England) 
[normal]that a permit scheme, previously submitted to the Secretary of State for approval, may be approved with or without modifications. Section 34(4) provides that a permit scheme shall not have effect unless the 
[normal]Secretary of State
[normal] gives effect to it by 
[normal]order
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]191.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The changes made by the Bill provide local highway authorities with a new power to give effect to permit schemes by order. The new power is exercisable in relation to 
[normal]England only.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]192.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause, by the insertion of Part 1 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 8 to the Bill makes certain amendments to Part 3 of the Traffic Management Act 2004. A new section 33A (Implementation of local highway authority permit schemes: England) is inserted into Part 3 and replaces the requirement for the Secretary of State to give effect to a local highway authority permit scheme, by requiring that the local highway authority give effect by 
[normal]order
[normal] to a permit scheme in its area. 
[normal]The authority can also vary or revoke a permit scheme by order. 
[normal]Such an 
[normal]order
[normal] will be a local council 
[normal]order
[normal], which will not be a statutory instrument.  Accordingly, local highway authorities will be able to prepare and give effect to their own permit schemes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]193.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The requirement for the Secretary of State to approve permit schemes is no longer required, given the generally high quality and consistency of such schemes. Providing local highway authorities with the ability to prepare and approve their own schemes is consistent with the principles of localism and removes an additional and unnecessary administrative layer which has resource considerations for the Secretary of State and local highway authorities. As local highway authorities will, in accordance with the 
[normal]clause, prepare their own permit schemes it is entirely logical that they give effect to such schemes, as the Secretary of State will no longer have an approval role. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]194.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 39(2) of the Traffic Management Act provides for the Secretary of State’s current power to make an 
[normal]order
[normal] giving effect to a permit 
[normal]scheme  to
[normal] be exercisable by statutory instrument. No parliamentary process is prescribed for such 
[normal]order
[normal]s and accordingly they are not laid before Parliament. Accordingly, although permit schemes will no longer be brought into effect by statutory instr
[normal]ument as there is currently no p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny of 
[normal]order
[normal]s made by the Secretary of State, the proposed ch
[normal]ange will not reduce or weaken p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny. Permit schemes will still be evidenced by a formal a
[normal]dministrative decision but the d
[normal]epartment considers that process should be placed in the hands of the authority that prepares and is to operate a permit scheme.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Clause 23(b) and [bold]Schedule[bold] 8, Part 2 – road humps[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Power conferred on: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]Secretary of State 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power exercised by: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory instrument
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parliamentary Procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]195.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Currently the Secretary of State has powers under section 90B of the Highways Act 1980 (
[normal]“
[normal]HA 1980
[normal]”
[normal]) to construct road humps. Local authorities also have these powers, by virtue of section 90A of the HA 1980. Paragraph 10 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 8 removes the Secretary of State’s powers. These powers are no longer necessary because in practice the construction of road humps is undertaken by local authorities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]196.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 90C of the HA 1980 sets down consultation requirements where there is a proposal to construct a road hump under section 90A or 90B (now to be repealed).  Section 90C(1) currently provides that there must be consultation with the chief officer of police and such other persons or bodies as may be prescribed by regulations made by the Secretary of State. These consultation requirements are amended by paragraph 11(2) of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 8. The reference to consultation with the chief officer of police is removed and the Secretary of State’s power to prescribe 
[normal]consultees
[normal] expanded in consequence to cover any persons or bodies (
[normal]ie
[normal] including the chief officer of police).
[normal]197.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 90C also sets out requirements about the publication of notices and the procedures for dealing with objections. There is an existing delegated power in the form of section 90C(5) of the HA 1980 which provides that, where, as the result of the receipt of objections, a local inquiry is held, provisions in the Local Government Act 1972 apply, but with such modifications as may be prescribed by regulations made by the Secretary of State.  The requirements about publicity and procedures for dealing with objections are amended by paragraph 11(3) of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 8.  They are replaced with a power for the Secretary of State to specify in regulations the requirements about publicity and procedures for dealing with objections.  This power includes the power to apply the relevant provisions of the Local Government Act 1972 about inquiries and to do so with specified modifications.
[normal]198.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 90D provides that the Secretary of State may by regulations make such provision in relation to the construction and maintenance of road humps as appears appropriate – for example, regulations about the size and maintenance of road humps etc. 
[normal]199.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 325 of the HA 1980 provides that powers to make regulations are 
[normal]exercisable
[normal] by statutory instrument and that an instrument containing regulations under section 90C or 90D is subject to the negative resolution procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]200.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]These powers are exercisable in relation to England and Wales. 
[normal]The department is
[normal] giving further consideration to whether it is appropriate for the changes to apply in relation to Wales.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the provision
[normal]201.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The amendments of section 90C made by paragraph 11(3) have the effect of enabling secondary legislation to make provision about matters which are currently prescribed (in the main) in primary legislation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]202.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is now considered more appropriate to make provision in secondary legislation, as opposed to on the face of the HA 1980, about the publicity requirements and the requirements for dealing with objections where there is a proposal to construct a road hump. This will give the flexibility to revise the requirements from time to time, including 
[normal]to take
[normal] account of developments in methods of communications.  At the moment, section 
[normal]90C(
[normal]2) provides for publication of a notice in one or more newspapers circulating in the area of the highway authority and at appropriate points on the highway.  Alternative or additional and more advanced methods of giving publicity to the proposal may in future be considered to be appropriate.  Similar provisions relating to traffic calming matters are made using secondary legislation.  This is an opportunity to standardise the procedure.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny
[normal]203.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As with the existing regulation making powers conferred by sections 90C and 90D of the HA 1980, it is considered appropriate for the new regulation making power being substituted into section 
[normal]90C(
[normal]2) of the HA 1980 to be subject to the negative resolution procedure.  It is a narrow power, concerned with detailed procedural points, where specialist traffic management knowledge and expertise may be required.  The negative resolution procedure is regarded as the appropriate level of parliamentary scrutiny.   
[normal]  
[normal]              
[normal]Clause 23(e) and [bold]Schedule[bold] 8, Part 5: [bold]Reduction of burdens relating to the use of roads and railways: Testing of vehicles[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parliamentary procedur
[normal]e: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]204.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Part 5 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 8 extends the Secretary of State’s regulation-making powers in relation to the roadworthiness testing of buses, coaches and 
[normal]lorries
[normal] by amending sections 46 and 51 of the Road Traffic Act 1988.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]205.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Sections 45 and 49 of the Road Traffic Act 1988 allow the Secretary of State to make provision by regulations for the examination of vehicles submitted for roadworthiness testing. In the case of section 45 these are any vehicles other than prescribed classes of goods vehicles and in the case of section 49 are prescribed classes of goods vehicles.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]206.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Sections 46 and 51 provide for what may in particular be made by regulations under sections 45 and 49 respectively. 
[normal]207.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]These powers are exercisable in relation to England and Wales and Scotland
[normal].
[normal]The effect of 
[normal]the provision
[normal]208.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Paragraph 16(2) to (4) amends section 46 and paragraph 17(2) to (4) amend section 51. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]209.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Paragraphs 16(2) and 17(2) allow provision to be made for charges to be paid to the Secretary of State by those occupying premises which are designated as stations for the roadworthiness testing of vehicles; namely, public service vehicles (i.e. buses and coaches carrying paying passengers) in the case of paragraph 16(2) and prescribed 
[normal]classes of goods vehicles (i.e. those over 3.5 tonnes) in the case of paragraph 17(2). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]210.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The charges may be in connection with the Secretary of State’s provision of vehicle examiners; the issue of test certificates or notifications of the refusal of test certificates; the issue of duplicate or copy test certificates and the correction of errors in test certificates. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]211.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Paragraphs 16(3) and (4) and 17(3) allow provision to be made for the occupiers of vehicle testing stations (for public service vehicles in the case of paragraph 16(3) and (4) and for prescribed classes of goods vehicles in the case of paragraph 17(3)) to keep registers of test certificates in the prescribed form and containing the prescribed particulars, for the inspection of those registers by prescribed persons in prescribed circumstances and for occupiers of such stations to keep records and provide returns and information to the Secretary of State.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]212.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Paragraph 17(4) allows, in relation to the roadworthiness testing of goods vehicles, provision to be made to require amounts in respect of charges in connection with the Secretary of State’s provision of vehicle examiners, the issue of test certificates or notifications of t
[normal]he refusal of test certificates, 
[normal]the issue of duplicate or copy test certificates or the correction of errors in test certificates to be paid to the Secretary of State on account and to allow the repayment of such amounts in prescribed circumstances. This paragraph also amends section 51 to allow provision to be made requiring payment 
[normal]to 
[normal]the Secretary of State of charges for the supply of forms for test certificates and notifications of refusal of test certificates and to allow the repayment of such charges in prescribed circumstances.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]213.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Paragraph 16(2) to (4) expands the existing powers to make regulations under sections 45 and 46 and paragraph 17(2)
[normal] 
[normal]to (4) expands the existing regulation-making powers in sections 49 and 51. The department continues to consider that the power to make provision by regulation for the examination of vehicles submitted for roadworthiness testing should be delegated to the Secretary of State. The detail of such provisions is more appropriate to secondary legislation. There is also likely to be a need to amend such provisions and make further provision from time to time which would be less conveniently achieved if contained in primary legislation.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny
[normal]214.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The negative resolution procedure applies, by virtue of section 195(3) of the Road Traffic Act 1988, to the existing powers to make regulations under sections 45 and 46 and 49 and 51 and the department continues to believe that this i
[normal]s appropriate. There 
[normal]should be p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny as the new powers extend to matters which include charging but these are not so significant as to merit the affirmative procedure. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Clause 23(f) and [bold]Schedule[bold] 8 Part 6: vehicle accessibility regulations – exemption [bold]order[bold]s [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on: 
[normal]              
[normal]N
[normal]o new power conferred; relates to current power exercisable by Secretary of State. 
[normal]Power exercised by: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Administrative 
[normal]order
[normal] 
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]N
[normal]one. 
[normal]Introduction
[normal]215.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Part 6 does not introduce a new delegated power, but amends the procedure that applies to an existing exemption 
[normal]order
[normal] making power. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]216.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 183(1) of the Equality Act 2010 enables the Secretary of State by 
[normal]order
[normal] to grant exemptions from rail vehicle accessibility regulations (RVAR). 
[normal]Currently the scrutiny procedure for an exemption 
[normal]order
[normal] is either the affirmative or negative procedure. The Secretary of State decides, on the basis set out in the Rail Vehicle Accessibility Exemption 
[normal]Order
[normal]s (Parliamentary Procedures) Regulations 2008, which procedure will apply. 
[normal]217.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]These powers are exercisable in relation to England and Wales and Scotland
[normal].
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]218.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Part 6 will amend the 2010
[normal] Act so that exemption 
[normal]order
[normal]s no longer need to be made by statutory instrument but can instead be made and amended by administrative 
[normal]order
[normal]s issued by the Secretary of State.  Consequently the parliamentary scrutiny procedures that currently apply to exemption 
[normal]order
[normal]s will no longer apply. 
[normal]219.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The principal benefit of Part 6 will be to reduce the resources required by 
[normal]the department 
[normal]in processing exemption applications to their conclusions.  This is because the resources needed to produce an administrative 
[normal]order
[normal] will be less than those required for preparing a statutory instrument and taking it through the parliamentary scrutiny process. The change will also save parliamentary time. In addition the 
[normal]department 
[normal]expects there to be a small benefit to applicants from the change by speeding up the process, so giving a decision sooner.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the use of administrative 
[normal]order and the level of p
[normal]arlia
[normal]mentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]220.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The scope of RVAR has been reduced since a similar proposal was made in the past (see below), such that they no longer apply to rail vehicles that are subject instead to EU accessibility rules. These rules require new, upgraded or renewed vehicles to comply with the technical specifications for interoperability for persons with reduced mobility (PRM TSI). The EU accessibility regime applies to mainline services, i.e. the majority of train services. RVAR now applies only to a minority (approximately one quarter) of rail vehicles – mostly light rail such as tramways, metros and underground. The two regulatory regimes have similar technical requirements.
[normal]221.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The EU accessibility regime is implemented in the UK by the Railways (Interoperability) Regulations 2011. One difference between the two regimes is that exemptions from RVAR are made by statutory instrument, while exemptions from the PRM TSI can 
[normal]by
[normal] made in Great Britain by the Secretary of State making an administrative determination, subject in some cases to the approval of the European Commission – see regulation 14 of the 2011 Regulations. Removing the requirement for RVAR exemption 
[normal]order
[normal]s to be made by statutory instrument will therefore bring the light rail regime more in line with the EU regime, which we believe is more proportionate, particularly given that other safeguards will remain.
[normal]222.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The requirement in the Equality Act 2010 for the Secretary of State to consult the Disabled Persons Transport Advisory Committee (DPTAC
[normal]) before granting an exemption is unchanged, as is the requirement for him to make an Annual Report to Parliament on the use of the exemption powers.  
[normal]The department
[normal] believe
[normal]s
[normal] that DPTAC’s continued involvement in considering the merits of each application will ensure that the needs of disabled people are given appropriate weight, while the Annual Report will allow Parliament to consider whether the powers had been used excessively in the past year and call Ministers to account if it so wished.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]223.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]department
[normal] made clear during consultation that there would be no reduction in the strength of argument required before an exemption was granted.  More background information about the proposal is set out in the 
[normal]department
[normal]’s March 2013 consultation, which can be found with a summary of the consultation responses at:
[normal]https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/proposed-changes-to-exemptions-from-rail-vehicle-accessibility-requirements
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]224.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A large majority of those who responded to the consultation supported the proposal, including DPTAC.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]225.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A similar proposal was made when the Disability Discrimination Bill was considered by Parliament before it became the Disability Discrimination Act 2005. That similar proposal was considered by the Delegated Powers and Regulatory Reform Committee and the Committee recommended that the proposal was not enacted - see paragraph 9 of the Committee’s Fourth Report for the Session 2004-5. In the end the Disability Discrimination Act 2005 amended the Disability Discrimination Act 1995 maintaining the requirement for parliamentary scrutiny in all circumstances, with the procedure being either the negative or affirmative procedure. The rail vehicle accessibility provisions of Disability Discrimination Acts, without significant further change, were re-enacted in the Equality Act 2010.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]226.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In its Fourth Report for the Session 2004-5 the Committee was concerned about the lack of evidence to support the proposal – see paragraph 7. The 
[normal]department 
[normal]now considers that it does have sufficient evidence and in particular points to the improved efficiency in public administration and the predominately supportive responses to the proposal following the recent consultation. An impact assessment for this measure will be available before introduction of the Bill to Parliament.  The 
[normal]department 
[normal]also believes that the large reduction in the scope of RVAR that has taken place since th
[normal]e proposal was first considered
[normal] justifies looking at this issue again. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Clause 28: Model clauses in petroleum licences: procedural simplification[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory instrument, or publication of a document
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution, or none
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]227.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause provides the Secretary of State with an additional method for changing the model clauses for petroleum licences.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]228.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 2 of the Petroleum Act 1998 (a Consolidation Act) provides that Her Majesty has the exclusive right of searching for and boring and getting petroleum which exists in its natural condition in strata in Great Britain. Her Majesty has similar rights in respect of petroleum in areas of the UK which are outside territorial waters, by virtue of section 1(1) of the Continental Shelf Act 1964. Section 3 of the 1998 Act authorises the Secretary of State, acting on behalf of Her Majesty, to grant licences to others to bore for and get the petroleum referred to in both Acts. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]229.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 4 of the 1998 Act places a duty on the Secretary of State to make regulations concerning various aspects of petroleum licences, such as the content and procedure for licence applications, licence fees, the areas in respect of which applications can be made and model clauses to be incorporated in licences. Regulations made under section 4 are subject to the negative resolution procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]230.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The model clauses set out in regulations must be included in licences unless the Secretary of State thinks that they should be modified or excluded in any particular case. The model clauses have been amended over time, and so petroleum licences issued at different times contain different clauses. The model clauses for all licences granted before 5th March 2004 can be found in consolidated form in the Petroleum (Current Model Clauses) 
[normal]Order
[normal] 1999 (S.I. 1999/160) and in  the Petroleum (Production) (Landward Areas) Regulations 1995 (S.I. 1995/1436). The model clauses for more recently issued licences are contained in, or determined by reference to, regulations made in S.I. 2004/352, 2006/784, 2008/225, 2009/2814 and 2009/3283.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]231.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The power is exercisable in respect of licences to search and bore for 
[normal]petroleum 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]in
[normal] strata in England and Wales, Scotland, the territorial sea adjacent to the UK and the UK sector of the continental shelf”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]232.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause amends section 4 of the 1998 Act in respect of the duty to make model clauses. It removes the current duty, in paragraph (1)(e), to prescribe model clauses in regulations and replaces it with new subsections (2A), (2B) and (2C) which provide that the Secretary of State must still prescribe model clauses, but may do so either in regulations or in a published document. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]233.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Where the duty is discharged by prescribing model clauses in regulations, the negative resolution procedure will continue to used, by virtue of section 4(3) of the 1998 Act as amended by subsection (5) of the clause. Where the duty is discharged by prescribing m
[normal]odel clauses in a document, no p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny procedure would apply.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]234.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The power to determine the terms of petroleum licences has been a delegated power since the introduction of petroleum licensing in the Petroleum (Production) Act 1934. The department continues to consider that it is appropriate to delegate this power to the Secretary of State. It enables the licensor to set new terms of licences which reflect the most up-to-date technical and commercial practices, where a need to use primary legislation would inevitably lead to delay and difficulty in keeping up with developments. It is a common feature of all regulated industries for the regulator – in this case the Secretary of State – to be given the power to determine the conditions of licences.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]235.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The department considers that although the model clauses of petroleum licences are important, 
[normal]they are not so important that p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny is required in respect of all changes to them. The grant of an energy licence is an administrative act, and the model clauses do not set out matters that have proved to be controversial or of wider interest.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]236.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The generally more controversial aspects of petroleum extraction are regulated in other ways – through health and safety legislation, through environmental regulation, through the planning system and through the tax regime. The relevant regimes are set out in primary and secondary legislation 
[normal]with the appropriate degree of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]237.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As a result, the department does not consider that the additional cost, procedural hurdles and occup
[normal]ation of p
[normal]arliamentary time associated with the making of statutory instruments are appropriate in every case; the amendments will enable the Secretary of State to act more swiftly where necessary, and at lower overall cost to the public purse. They will also make it easier for the Secretary of State to publish fully consolidated copies of the model clauses with greater regularity – the resources required to make consolidating statutory instruments, and the costs associated with making large instruments, currently act as a disincentive to regular consolidation exercises. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]238.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The amendments will allow the Secretary of State to include model clauses in regulations, using the negative resolution procedure, wherever it is considered appropriate because the changes are controversial or because they implement a significant change of policy. It is very difficult to predict at this stage when changes to model clauses will fall on one side of the line or the other when assessing how significant they are. But the department anticipates that it will be clearer when individual issues are being considered whether model clauses ought to be prescribed in regulations, taking into account consultat
[normal]ion responses and the level of p
[normal]arliamentary interest at the time. Where minor and technical amendments are being made, publication in a document is likely to be the preferable procedure. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Clause 29 and [bold]Schedule[bold] 10: household waste: de-criminalisation[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Power conferred on: 
[normal]              
[normal]The Secretary of State; the Lord Chancellor 
[normal]Power exercised by: 
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory instrument; 
[normal]order
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]239.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Environmental Protection Act 1990 (“the 1990 Act”) enables a waste collection authority (“a WCA”) by notice to require the occupier of premises to place household waste for collection in receptacles of a kind and number specified (section 46). Failure, without reasonable excuse, to comply with such requirements is an offence currently punishable with a fine of up to £1000 (section 46(6)).
[normal]240.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As an alternative to prosecution, an authorised officer of a WCA may offer the opportunity of discharging any liability to conviction by payment of a fixed penalty (section 47ZA). The amount of such a penalty is the amount specified by the WCA in relation to its area, or, if no amount is so specified, £60 for offences in England (the ‘default’ amount). The WCA may make provision for treating the penalty as having been paid if a lesser amount is paid before the end of a specified period. The Secretary of State may by regulations make provision in connection with those powers of the WCA, and also has power by 
[normal]order
[normal] to substitute a different amount for the ‘default’ amount (section 47ZB).
[normal]241.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The London Local Authorities Act 2007 (“the 2007 Act”) enables a London borough council to make regulations requiring occupiers of premises to place household waste for collection in receptacles of a kind and number specified (section 20). Unlike the 1990 Act, failure to comply with such requirements is not an offence, although a penalty charge is payable by any occupier of premises in respect of which there has been a failure, without reasonable excuse, to comply with any requirements imposed by such regulations (section 23). 
[normal]242.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is the duty of the borough councils to set the levels of penalty charges, but they do not come into force until the Secretary of State has been notified and does not object to them on the ground that they are excessive. If, at any time before the levels of fixed penalties have come into force, the Secretary of State does consider them excessive, the Secretary of State may make regulations setting the levels of fixed penalties (sections 66 and 67). 
[normal]243.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In relation to appeals, section 62 provides that the Lord Chancellor has the power to make provision by regulations relating to an appeal to an adjudicator if a person’s representations to a borough council are not accepted. No such regulations have yet been made, and section 62 goes on to provide that, until such time as regulations are in force, any regulations under section 80 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 shall, with any necessary modifications, apply in relation to representations, appeals and adjudicators as if made under the corresponding provisions of the 2007 Act.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]244.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The delegated powers conferred by the clause and Schedule are exercisable in relation to 
[normal]England only.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]245.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause amends the 1990 Act to remove, in England, the criminal offence under section 46(6). In place of the fixed penalty system available as an alternative to prosecution, this clause also introduces, in England, a more proportionate sanction for non-compliance, by making provision for the imposition
[normal] of a fixed monetary penalty in 
[normal]cases where a specified threshold is reached and procedural safeguards have been met. The amount of such a penalty is the amount specified by the WCA in relation to its area (new section 
[normal]46B(
[normal]1)(a)), or, if no amount is so specified, £60 (new section 46B(1)(b)). A WCA may make provision for treating a fixed penalty as having been paid if a lesser amount is paid before the end of a period specified by the authority (new section 46B(2)).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]246.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As part of the amendments to the 1990 Act, this clause confers on the Secretary of State the power, by regulations, to make provision in connection with the powers conferred on waste collection authorities under new section 46B(1)(a) and (2) (new section 46B(3)). In particular, such regulations may require an amount specified by the WCA to fall within a range prescribed in the regulations, and may restrict the extent to which, and the circumstances in which, a WCA can make provision under new section 
[normal]46B(
[normal]2). The amendments made by this clause also confer on the Secretary of State the power, by 
[normal]order
[normal], to substitute a different amount for the amount for the time being specified in subsection (1)(b) (i.e. the ‘default’ amount) (new section 46B(5)). 
[normal]247.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause and 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 10 amend the 2007 Act for the purposes of ensuring a degree of consistency between the penalty systems relating to household waste under the 1990 Act and the 2007 Act. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]248.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The amendments provide that a London borough council may require a person to pay a penalty charge for a failure to comply with requirements (imposed by regulations made under section 20(1)) relating to household waste receptacles (new section 20A). It is the duty of the borough councils to set the levels of penalty charges payable to them under section 20A (new section 
[normal]20B(
[normal]1)), and the borough councils may make provision for treating a penalty charge as having been paid if a lesser amount is received by the relevant council before the end of a period specified by the borough councils (new section 20B(3)).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]249.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]New section 20B(4) confers on the Secretary of State the power, by regulations, to make provision in connection with the functions conferred on the borough councils under new subsection 20B(1) and (3). In particular, such regulations may require the levels of penalty charges to fall within a range prescribed in the regulations, and may restrict the extent to which, and the circumstances in which, the borough councils can make provision under subsection (3).
[normal]250.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]New section 20D makes provision relating to appeals against decisions to impose penalty charges. These extend the existing system of appeals provided for by the 2007 Act to the revised penalty charge system provided for by this clause. Subsection (1) 
[normal]confers on the Lord Chancellor power to include in regulations made under the existing power in section 62(2) provision relating to appeals to an adjudicator against a decision under section 20A to require a person to pay a penalty charge. Subsection (2) confers on the Secretary of State a power, exercisable by regulations, to prescribe modifications to the application of regulations under section 80 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 in relation to appeals against decisions to impose penalty charges  (subsection (2) applies regulations under section 80 until such time as regulations made by the Lord Chancellor are in force).
[normal]Ju
[normal]stification of the delegation
[normal]251.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The amendments to the 1990 Act conferring power to make provision in connection with the powers conferred on WCAs in England in relation to
[normal] the amount of any penalty and 
[normal]to make provi
[normal]sion for early payment, and to 
[normal]amend the ‘default’ amount, give the Secretary of State 
[normal]powers
[normal] which are similar to those currently provided for by the 1990 Act. These powers enable the Secretary of State to exercise a degree of control over the amount of any fixed penalty that a WCA may impose (for example, by setting a range into which any fixed penalty must fall). The department considers it appropriate to continue the Secretary of State’s ability to exercise a degree of control over the amount of any fixed penalty that a WCA may impose under the new system of fixed penalties – this also enables the amounts to be “future proofed” to an extent, without the need for primary legislation when the amounts need to be changed. In 
[normal]order
[normal] to enable a degree of consistency between the penalty levels and systems under the 1990 Act and the 2007 Act, the department considers that it is also appropriate to give the Secretary of State similar powers under the 2007 Act to make provision in connection with the powers conferred on London borough councils in relation t
[normal]o the amount of any penalty and
[normal] to make provision for early payment (there is no ‘default’ amount in the 2007 Act).
[normal]252.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The department considers that the powers conferred on the Lord Chancellor and the Secretary of State in relation to appeals under the 2007 Act are a necessary consequence of extending the existing appeals system to take account of the amendments made by this clause. The Lord Chancellor already has power to make provision by regulations relating to appeals (section 62), and this power is extended to enable the revised penalty charge provision introduced by this clause to work properly within the existing appeal structure set out in the 2007 Act. Similarly, the amendments made by this clause to apply (until such time as regulations made by the Lord Chancellor are in force) regulations under section 80 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 in relation to appeals continues the existing approach taken by the 2007 Act; the department considers that the additional power conferred to enable the Secretary of State to prescribe modifications to those regulations is necessary to ensure that the application of such regulations works properly.
[normal]Justification of the level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny
[normal]253.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]All the powers conferred by this clause and 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 10 are to be exercised by statutory instrument subject to negative procedure (in relation to the 1990 Act, by virtue of section 161 of that Act; in relation to the 2007 Act, by virtue of section 82 of that Act). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]254.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The powers conferred by way of amendment to the 1990 Act relate to the setting of amounts for fixed penalties rather than the circumstances in which fixed penalties may be imposed. They replace similar powers which were subject to negative procedure. Given the limited scope of the powers, the department considers that it is appropriate for their exercise to be subject to negative procedure (the similar powers which are replaced were also subject to negative procedure). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]255.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In relation to the powers conferred by way of amendment to the 2007 Act, the power of the Lord Chancellor exercisable under section 62(2) of that Act (relating to appeals) is already exercisable by way of negative procedure, so an extension of that power by virtue of the new section 
[normal]20D(
[normal]1) of that Act to cover different circumstances should, in the department’s view, be similarly dealt with. The power of the Secretary of State under new section 20B(4) relates to the setting of amounts for fixed penalties rather than the circumstances in which those penalties may be imposed and, as with the changes to the 1990 Act, the department considers that it is appropriate for the exercise of such power to be subject to negative procedure. The power of the Secretary of State to make modifications to the applicability of regulations made under section 80 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 is something which, as a consequential and technical provision, the department considers is suitably scrutinised by means of negative procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Clause 30 and [bold]Schedule[bold] 11, paragraph 1: power to extend provisions of Destructive Imported Animals Act 1932 to other destructive non-indigenous animals[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
