[normal]Introduction
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]256.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause loosens the precondition applying before Ministers may make an 
[normal]order
[normal] under section 10 of the Destructive Imported Animals Act 1932.  By 
[normal]section 1 of that Act, Ministers are currently empowered to prohibit, or control by licensing, the importation into, and keeping within, Great Britain of musk rats.  By section 10(1) of the Act, Ministers are currently further empowered to make any such 
[normal]order
[normal] as they are capable of making with respect to musk rats so as to apply with respect to any other non-indigenous mammalian species – but only where Ministers are satisfied that by reason of their destructive habits “it is desirable to prohibit or control the importation or keeping of them and to destroy any which may be at large”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Devolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]257.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]These powers are exercisable in relation to England and Wales. This area is devolved to Wales. The amendments affect the existing powers of both the Secretary of State and the Welsh Ministers. The department is discussing the need for a legislative consent 
[normal]motion  with
[normal] the devolved administration. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]258.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The provision contained in paragraph 1(2) of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 11 of the Bill now dilutes the precondition that Ministers must first be satisfied that any members at large (of a species in respect of which they propose to make an 
[normal]order
[normal] under section 10(1)) should be destroyed. By virtue of the amendment, it is, in the alternative, sufficient for Ministers to “
[normal]keep under review whether any which may be at large should be destroyed”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]259.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Additionally, the provision
[normal] (a new s.10(1A))
[normal] contained in paragraph 1(3) of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 11 now 
[normal]ensures beyond all doubt that
[normal] the power to make an 
[normal]order
[normal] under section 10(1)
[normal] 
[normal]also includes the power to revoke or amend such an 
[normal]order
[normal]. Doubt as to this had arisen because, in relation to Acts passed after 1889 but before the commencement of the Interpretation Act 1978, the power under section 14 of that Act to revoke, amend or re-enact instruments only extended to rules, regulations and bye-laws (see paragraph 3 of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2 to that Act).  Section 10(1) DIAA contains an 
[normal]order
[normal]-making power, so is not expressly caught by section 14.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]260.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The delegated power already exists; but the precondition to its use has been slightly loosened so that it refers to the 
[normal]order
[normal]-maker being satisfied that it is desirable 
[normal]either
[normal] to destroy any animals of the
[normal] species which may be at large (the current requirement) or (new)
[normal] to keep under review whether such animals should be destroyed.  
[normal]This is because there may be situations and species (such as the grey squirrel) where the promotion of a policy of destruction is currently deemed impractical, but it is still wished to be able to impose the Act’s controls on that species’ importation and keeping.
[normal]&#xa0;
