[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]264.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 14(4) currently requires maintained schools 
[normal]to make copies of Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector of Education, Children’s Services and Skills inspection reports available to the public and to provide a copy of the report to parents of the pupils of the school, 
[normal]free of charge. Schools must also provide the report to any other person who asks for one and, in prescribed cases, may request payment from those persons of such fee as they think fit (not exceeding the cost of supply).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]265.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 49(4) of the Education Act 2005 places a similar duty on foundation and voluntary schools which have a religious character, in respect of reports of inspections under section 48 of that Act (inspection of religious education). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]266.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Since September 2012 maintained schools have been required to publish i
[normal]nformation as to where and by what means parents may access the most recent report about the school published by her Majesty’s Chief Inspector of Education, Children’s Services and Skills 
[normal]under the School Information (England) Regulations 2008 (S.I. No. 3093) (“the School Information Regulations”).
[normal] In practice in 
[normal]order
[normal] to comply schools are likely to publish 
[normal]a link to any 
[normal]Ofsted
[normal] reports on their website
[normal].
[normal] For that reason, it is considered appropriate to revoke the current requirements in section 14(4) of the Education Act 2005. The duty to publish the school inspection reports which the School Information Regulations place on maintained schools renders the current requirements at section 14(4) superfluous and burdensome on schools. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]267.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Religious inspection reports are published on faith body websites and therefore are already accessible to parents and others. In addition, paragraph 6(5) of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 14 amends the School Information Regulations by inserting a new duty (at new paragraph 3A of 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 4 to those Regulations) for 
[normal]foundation or voluntary
[normal] schools
[normal] which have a religious character
[normal] to publish 
[normal]information as to where and by what means parents may access the most recent report about the school sent to the governing body under section 
[normal]49 of the Education Act 2005. As above it is probable that schools will comply by publishing 
[normal]a link to the reports on their website. Removing the current duty at section 49(4) will reduce administrative costs. 
[normal]&#xa0;
