[normal] 
[normal]This is set 
[normal]out  at
[normal] section 121(1) of the Education Act 2005. Like the previous regulation-making powers, the details which those regulations will prescribe relate to a purely procedural matter prescribing how quickly schools must notify parents of the result of an inspection.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 36 Criminal procedure: written witness statements[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Criminal Procedure Rule Committee
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Criminal Procedure Rules
[normal]Parliamentary proc
[normal]edure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]274.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause allows Criminal Procedure Rules, made under sections 69 and 72 of the Courts Act 2003, (
[normal]i
[normal]) to extend the period during which a party to criminal proceedings may object to another party using the written statement of a witness, instead of calling the witness to give evidence in person; and (ii) to provide the supplementary procedure where a written statement is used.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]275.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 9 of the Criminal Justice Act 1967 provides that in criminal proceedings the written statement of a witness shall be ‘admissible as evidence to the like extent as oral evidence to the like effect by that person’, if the conditions listed in that section are met. The conditions include requirements for a declaration by the witness, for signature by the witness, for the way in which the written statement must be delivered to (in the language of the Act, be ‘served on’) the other parties, for the way in which it must be presented to the court and, crucially, a requirement that none of those on whom the statement has been served has objected within 7 days. The section applies equally to prosecution and defence witnesses. In practice, it is the most commonly encountered provision by which evidence other than oral testimony is admitted in criminal proceedings. This clause amends that section.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]276.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The new delegated power
[normal] 
[normal]conferred by the clause is 
[normal]exercisable in relation to England and Wales
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the provision
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]277.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The amendment made by clause 36(3) means that, where a written statement is served, other parties will never have less than the current 7 days in which to object, but Criminal Procedure Rules will be able to extend that period, in specified circumstances or generally. The point of allowing for a longer period is to remove any perceived need to enter a ‘holding’ objection, so as to keep the objector’s options open while they assess the statement. Objections can be withdrawn before the trial takes place, but experience demonstrates that that often is overlooked, with the result that witnesses attend court 
[normal]when they need not have done. A longer time limit for objection would remove the need to object just out of caution.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]278.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Criminal Procedure Rules already provide generally for the content and service of documents in criminal proceedings, and for the way in which evidence and other material is presented to the court. Section 9 of the 1967 Act, passed long before the Criminal Procedure Rules first came into force in 2005, contains procedural requirements that constrain what the Rules can provide in relation to written witness statements. The repeals made by clause 36(4) mean that the Rules will be able to 
[normal]provide  the
[normal] necessary supplementary procedure. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]279.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Criminal Procedure Rule Committee was established by the Courts Act 2003 specifically to make and maintain rules governing the practice and procedure of the criminal courts. The chairman is the Lord Chief Justice, and members are drawn from among those involved in the criminal justice system, including the judiciary, the legal professions, prosecutors, the police and voluntary organisations. It is independent of government. The amendments made by this clause confer on the Committee an additional power consistent with its existing statutory responsibilities. This helps to ensure that criminal procedure is consistent and easy to find, 
[normal]and  makes
[normal] it possible for the Criminal Procedure Rule Committee to keep that procedure up to date and efficient in the light of experience.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]280.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Significant safeguards (such as the right to object to the introduction of written evidence and the minimum period for objection) will remain on the face of the 1967 Act. Section 72 of the Courts Act 2003 requires that Criminal Procedure Rules must be allowed by the Lord Chancellor and must be contained in a statutory instrument subject to annulment by resolution of either House of Parliament. This clause concerns only criminal procedure, and contains nothing that might justify an
[normal]y more searching scrutiny. The p
[normal]arliamentary procedure for which section 72 provides therefore is justified.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 37 Criminal procedure: written guilty pleas[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Criminal Procedure Rule Committee
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Criminal Procedure Rules
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]281.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause allows Criminal Procedure Rules, made under sections 69 and 72 of the Courts Act 2003, to dispense with the present requirement for written material to be read aloud to magistrates where the defendant pleads guilty without attending court and where the magistrates can read the documents for themselves.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]282.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Sections 12 and 12A of the Magistrates’ Courts Act 1980 allow a defendant to plead guilty in writing without attending court. The procedure can be used only for comparatively minor offences, and only where certain procedural requirements have been met. The procedure is widely used in minor road traffic cases and for TV licence evasion, for example. Even though the parties are absent and the court deals with the case on the papers, section 12 requires the prosecution case and the defence representations to be read aloud to the magistrates.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]283.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The new delegated power
[normal] 
[normal]conferred by the clause is
[normal] exercisable in relation to England and Wales.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]284.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause amends section 12 of the 1980 Act. Criminal Procedure Rules will be able to specify what, if 
[normal]anything,
[normal] need be read aloud, and in what circumstances. Though the parties themselves are absent, the proceedings are still a trial and members of the public may be present. The point of allowing rules to dispense with some or all of the current requirements is so that they can provide for the prompt and efficient disposal of court business in a way that is consistent with the defendant’s right to a fair trial and with the principles of open justice.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]285.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Criminal Procedure Rule Committee was established by the Courts Act 2003 specifically to make and maintain rules governing the practice and procedure of the criminal courts. The chairman is the Lord Chief Justice, and members are drawn from among those involved in the criminal justice system, including the judiciary, the legal professions, prosecutors, the police and voluntary organisations. It is independent of government. The amendments made by this clause confer on the Committee an additional power consistent with its existing statutory responsibilities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]286.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The safeguards limiting the types of offences which can be dealt with under section 12 of the 1980 Act will remain in that section. Section 72 of the Courts Act 2003 requires 
[normal]that Criminal Procedure Rules must be allowed by the Lord Chancellor and must be contained in a statutory instrument subject to annulment by resolution of either House of Parliament. This clause concerns only criminal procedure, and contains nothing that might justify an
[normal]y more searching scrutiny. The p
[normal]arliamentary procedure for which section 72 provides therefore is justified.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 38 Criminal procedure: powers to make Criminal Procedure Rules[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Criminal Procedure Rule Committee
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Criminal Procedure Rules
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]287.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause allows Criminal Procedure Rules, made under sections 69 and 72 of the Courts Act 2003, to supply the procedure for five types of application to a judge, including provision for applications to be made by email or by other electronic means.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]288.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 2 of the Administration of Justice (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1933 allows a High Court judge to authorise the bringing of a prosecution in the Crown Court where, for some unusual reason, the case has not been 
[normal]sent
[normal] for trial by a magistrates’ court. 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 1 to the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 allows a Circuit judge to make a production 
[normal]order
[normal], or in some circumstances to issue a warrant, authorising an investigator to obtain access to some types of potential evidence that investigators are not entitled to seize under a search warrant issued by a justice of the peace. 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 5 to the Terrorism Act 2000, and section 352 of the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002, allow a Circuit judge to issue a warrant for the same purpose as under the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 but in connection with, respectively, a terrorism investigation or an investigation into the disposal of the proceeds of crime. Section 59 of the Criminal Justice and Police Act 2001 allows a Crown Court judge to make an 
[normal]order
[normal] for the return to its owner of property seized during an investigation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]289.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The new delegated
[normal] powers
[normal] conferred by the clause
[normal] are exercisable in relation to England and Wales.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]290.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The clause makes amendments to each of the above five Acts which will allow Criminal Procedure Rules to supply the necessary supplementary procedures.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]291.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Rules already provide for the procedure on similar applications under other statutory provisions. However, the Courts Act 2003 and the above five Acts are in slightly different terms, so that the Rules cannot yet govern the practice and procedure on applications under those particular provisions. Moreover, the 1984 Act contains procedural requirements that constrain what the Rules can provide in relation to applications for production orders under that Act. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]292.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Criminal Procedure Rule Committee was established by the Courts Act 2003 specifically to make and maintain rules governing the practice and procedure of the criminal courts. The chairman is the Lord Chief Justice, and members are drawn from among those involved in the criminal justice system, including the judiciary, the legal professions, prosecutors, the police and voluntary organisations. It is independent of government. The amendments made by this clause confer on the Committee additional powers consistent with its existing statutory responsibilities. The point of allowing the Rules to provide the supplementary procedures is to keep criminal procedure consistent and easy to find, and to make it possible for the Criminal Procedure Rule Committee to keep that procedure up to date and efficient in the light of experience.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]293.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The criteria for making the 
[normal]order
[normal]s with which this clause is concerned will remain in the five affected Acts. Section 72 of the Courts Act 2003 requires that Criminal Procedure Rules must be allowed by the Lord Chancellor and must be contained in a statutory instrument subject to annulment by resolution of either House of Parliament. This clause concerns only criminal procedure, and contains nothing that might justify an
[normal]y more searching scrutiny. The p
[normal]arliamentary procedure for which section 72 provides therefore is justified.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 41: Removal of restriction on persons who may manage child trust funds[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Treasury
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parl
[normal]iamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Negative R
[normal]esolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]294.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause provides for regulations to be made which will enable a wider range of organisations to be authorised to manage Child Trust Funds (“CTFs”) held by certain looked after children.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]295.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A CTF is a tax advantaged savings account held by an eligible child into which money up to a specified amount can be invested each year.  Until the account holder attains the age of 16, CTFs are managed on their behalf by a “registered contact” (for example, a person with parental responsibility for the account holder).  Special arrangements are set out in legislation for the management of CTFs held by certain looked after children.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]296.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 3(10) of the Child Trust Funds Act 2004 (“the Act”) provides that the Treasury may, by regulations, authorise the Official Solicitor (in England and Wales or Northern Ireland) or the Accountant of Court (in Scotland) to manage the CTFs of certain children.  Under the Child Trust Funds Regulations 2004 (“the CTF Regulations”) these persons are authorised to manage the CTFs of certain children who are looked after by local authorities, until someone with parental responsibility assumes that role or the child reaches the age of 16 and can personally manage their own account.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]297.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Section 16 of the Act enables regulations to be made requiring local authorities to provide certain information relating to a child to HMRC, where the child is in, or enters, the care of the local authority.  This power has been used to make regulation 33A of the CTF Regulations which provides for the circumstances in which the Official Solicitor or Accountant of Court is to have authority to manage the accounts of looked after children notified by local authorities to HMRC.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]298.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The delegated
[normal] 
[normal]powers conferred by the clause are exercisable in relation to England and
[normal] Wale
[normal]s, Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]299.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause amends section 3 of the Act (requirements to be satisfied) to provide that, in circumstances specified in regulations, the Treasury or the Secretary of State may authorise a person other than the Official Solicitor (of England and Wales or Northern Ireland) or the Accountant of Court (in Scotland) to manage the CTFs of certain looked after children.  This will enable a wider range of bodies to be authorised to manage the CTFs of certain looked after children, including, where appropriate, third sector organisations.  Such authorisation would be subject to the appointed person satisfying requirements as set out in the regulations and abiding by a formal agreement.  It is anticipated that any such arrangements for the management of
[normal] CTFs for looked after children
[normal] may be similar
[normal] to
[normal] those in place for the Junior ISA accounts of certain looked after children, which are managed by an authorised third sector organisation under an agreement with the Department for Education.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]300.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In addition, this clause amends section 16 of the Act (information about children in care of authority) so that regulations may place a requirement on local authorities to 
[normal]provide information relating to certain looked after children directly to the person so appointed by the Treasury or the Secretary of State for the purposes of facilitating the management of such CTFs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]301.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The power to make regulations under section 3(10) of the Act prescribing the circumstances whereby the Official Solicitor (of England and Wales or Northern Ireland) or the Accountant of Court (in Scotland) is authorised to manage the CTFs of certain looked after children is exercisable by the Treasury.  Similarly, section 16(1) empowers the Treasury to make regulations which may require authorities to provide to HMRC information relating to children in their care. These same powers, once amended by this clause, will enable regulations to be made by the Treasury which (
[normal]i
[normal]) provide for the circumstances in which the Treasury or the Secretary of State may authorise other persons to manage the CTFs of certain looked after children, and (ii) require local authorities to provide certain information to such an authorised person.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of p
[normal]arliamen
[normal]tary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]302.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Act currently provides that any regulations made under sections 3(10) and 16(1) of the Act are subject to the negative procedure pursuant to section 28(8). Other than in specified circumstances concerning a child’s eligibility for CTF or payments to a child’s account, all regulations making provision of an administrative nature, such as management of accounts or provision of information, are made by negative procedure.  Further regulations made under the powers to be amended by this clause will continue to be subject to the negative procedure and the Treasury considers that the negative procedure continues to provide the appropriate degree of scrutiny.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 48: [bold]Ambulatory references to international shipping instruments[bold]Power conferred on: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Her Majesty in Council and/or Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Regulations made by s
[normal]tatutory instrument/Direction 
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Varies (as explained further below)
[normal]Introduction
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]303.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause amends the Merchant Shipping Act 1995 so that the powers to make secondary legislation wherever they appear in that Act can be exercised so as to provide for a reference in the legislation to an international agreement to be interpreted as a 
[normal]reference to the agreement as modified from time to time. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]304.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The current practice of implementing international maritime 
[normal]conventions,
[normal] and regular changes to them, by means of a mixture of primary legislation and secondary legislation has resulted in a complex regulatory structure that is confusing to industry and the regulator alike. It is also time consuming and resource intensive, leading to delays in implementation – which in turn can result in ships being challenged during inspections in foreign ports leading to delays and inconvenience to UK ships.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]305.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The clause has been designed to address these issues by making it possible to streamline the incorporation of the provisions of international maritime conventions so that, where it is considered appropriate to do so, the government would not need to make further secondary legislation or publish any other regulatory document in 
[normal]order
[normal] to give effect to changes to international obligations and standards; changes to the text of an international agreement would be automatically incorporated into UK law in the circumstances specified in the secondary legislation.
[normal]306.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This power 
[normal]is exercisable in relation to England and 
[normal]Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]307.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The clause provides that the existing powers to make secondary legislation contained in the Merchant Shipping Act may be exercised so as to make ambulatory provision.  It also provides that the operation of the ambulatory reference may be 
[normal]dis
[normal]-applied or delayed.  It is not proposed to consider each of the individual powers to make subordinate legislation affected, which are subject to different parliamentary procedures; some of which already allow what are in effect ambulatory references to be made in certain circumstances.  This memorandum will consider two issues.  The first being the principle of allowing ambulatory references in secondary legislation, the second being the power of direction provided for in subsection (5) which would have the effect of limiting the operation of the ambulatory reference.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]308.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The principle of allowing ambulatory references in legislation is now well established most notably in paragraph 1A(1) which was added to 
[normal]Schedule
[normal] 2 of the European Communities Act 1972 by section 28 of the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]309.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]International instruments in the marine sector such as SOLAS (the International Convention for the Safety of Life at Sea) and MARPOL (the International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution from Ships) are often of a highly technical nature specifying standards of construction, equipment and procedures that must be complied with.  
[normal]Because of the international nature of shipping operations once the provision come into force they must be complied with by the UK shipping industry where it operates in the territorial waters of a signatory country, irrespective of whether the UK has incorporated the relevant requirements into its domestic law.  In addition once the UK has become a party to an international instrument which has come into force it is under an obligation to apply the terms of that instrument both to its own ships and, usually, to ships of other nations operating within its jurisdiction.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]310.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In some cases therefore allowing a change to an international instrument to take effect through the operation of an ambulatory reference in the manner proposed in this clause represents the most timely and cost effective method of providing certainty to the industry and allowing the UK to comply with its international obligations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]311.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] Subsection (5) provides that secondary legislation may authorise the Secretary of State to give a direction wh
[normal]ich will have the effect of 
[normal]dis
[normal]applying
[normal] or delaying the operation of the ambulatory provision.  
[normal]Subsection (6) extends this power of direction to include 
[normal]disapplying
[normal] any provision of subordinate legislation to which the ambulatory provision relates and making alternative provis
[normal]i
[normal]on.
[normal] 
[normal]The reason that the
[normal]se
[normal] power
[normal]s are
[normal] being sought is that there may be occasions when it is necessary to delay or prevent an obligation which arises as a result of an ambulatory change from having effect 
[normal]and in
[normal] 
[normal]some cases make alternative provision
[normal].  Such instances are expected to be rare; an example might be where the new provision would be inconsistent with an existing EU law obligation which is likely to be the case where the EU adopts higher standards than are required by the international agreement.  
[normal]In such cases it would be important that the existing secondary legislation did not remain in force
[normal]. 
[normal]It would of course be possible to achieve the same result by amending the secondary legislation which gives effect to the ambulatory provision.  However, this is likely to be difficult to achieve in the required timescale particularly where the instrument requires the affirmative process and 
[normal]would be inconsistent with the g
[normal]overnment’s policy of reducing the number of statutory instruments required to implement the international obligations.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]312.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As far as the exercise of delegation conferred by the making of the ambulatory reference itself is concerned this will only be possible where there is an existing power to make secondary legislation.  The level of scrutiny appropriate to the subject matter of such legislation will have already been co
[normal]nsidered by Parliament and the d
[normal]epartment sees no reason why, if an ambulatory reference is to be included in such legislation
[normal],
[normal] that there should be any change to the level of scrutiny.  In a number of cases, particularly where the purpose of the legislation is to incorporate changes to the text of an international instrument, the secondary legislation is subject to the affirmative procedure.  Parliament will, in almost all such most cases, have the ability to consider the instrument containing the ambulatory reference under either the negative or affirmative procedure.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]313.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a further consideration which is that in most circumstances a change to UK law taking effect as a result of the operation of the ambulatory reference will only take effect following a change to an international agreement which will have been agreed to by the UK government and which will already been notified to Parliament. The only instances where this will not be are 
[normal]cases  where
[normal] the international instrument contains a process whereby supplemental provision can be made through the issue of a code or a standard or changes can be made to the terms of the instrument through the so called tacit agreement procedure whereby a change becomes effective and binds all the signatories of the agreement once a certain number of signatories have agreed.  However, in both cases the possibility of such changes being made without the further need for the explicit approval of the UK government was already present when the decision was made to accede to the agreement so this should not of itself demand additional scrutiny.   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]314.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As already noted to the extent that the power of the Secretary of State to issue directions 
[normal]under  subsection
[normal] (5) is novel this should not necessarily mean that any additional scrutiny is needed.  Firstly, the inclusion of the power in secondary legislation will of it
[normal]self be subject to the level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny that has already been considered appropriate for the relevant secondary legislation.  Secondly, the effect of the exercise of the power will 
[normal]normally 
[normal]be to preserve the existing le
[normal]gal position. As a result, the d
[normal]epartment does not consider the power should be subject to any additional procedure and that the additional cost, proced
[normal]ural hurdles and occupation of p
[normal]arliamentary time associated with the making of a statutory instruments would not be appropriate in this case; the power will enable the Secretary of State to act more swiftly where necessary, and at lower overall cost to the public purse.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 49 – power to spell out dates described in legislation[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]A Minister of the Crown
[normal]Power exercised by: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Order
[normal]  made
[normal] by statutory instrument
[normal]Parliamentary Procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]N
[normal]one
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]315.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Clause 49 confers a power on Ministers to amend legislation – primary and secondary - by statutory instrument in 
[normal]order
[normal] to spell out dates described in it. So, for example, if a section of an Act refers to “the day on which this section comes into force”, the power would allow the actual date to be substituted, when it becomes known. The amendments to be made by secondary legislation are therefore editorial rather than substantive.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]316.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The purpose of the power is to improve the accessibility of legislation, so that those reading legislation will be able to see on the face of the legislation what the relevant dates are without having to look them up, for example by searching through commencement 
[normal]order
[normal]s. The power can be used on an ongoing basis, in relation to legislation passed or made after the enactment of the Bill, to replace references to commencement dates with actual dates as and when they become known, but it will also be possible to use it to amend references to commencement dates in existing legislation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Devolution
[normal]317.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This 
[normal]power
[normal]  is
[normal] exercisable in relation to England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. The power could therefore be used to change references to commencement in legislation which deals with a matter devolved to Scotland, Northern Ireland or Wales. In the light of this, discussions are taking place with the devolved administrations to ascertain whether it would be appropriate for legislative consent motions to be sought in respect of clause 49. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]318.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The effect of this clause is to provide a flexible mechanism through which legislation can 
[normal]be  edited
[normal] to enable those reading it to readily understand when it came into force. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation
[normal]319.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is appropriate for the relevant amendments to be made by 
[normal]order
[normal] made by statutory instrument so that they are accessible and published in the statutory instrument series.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of parliamentary s
[normal]crutiny
[normal]320.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The proposed new power is not subject to any form of parliamentary procedure. This is because the amendments made using the power will not involve any substantive policy decisions but will reflect decisions made previously. Similar powers have been included in previous legislation – for example, clause 7(2) of the Offender Rehabilitation Bill introduced in the House of Lords on 9 May. This power was not subject to any form of parliamentary procedure.  The Delegated Powers and Regulatory Reform Committee in their Report on that Bill said “we welcome the facility introduced by clause 7(2
[normal])(
[normal]a), as we can see some real advantages for users of legislation in the replacement of references to commencement dates” (First Report of 2013/14; HL Paper 12). Clause 22(3) of the draft Pensions Bill, published on 2 January 2013, also included a similar power, although this was ultimately dropped as it became unnecessary.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause[bold]s  50[bold]-57[bold] – [bold]order[bold]s [bold]disapplying[bold] legislation no longer of practical use [bold]Power conferred on: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]A 
[normal]Minister of the Crown
[normal]Power exercised by: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Order
[normal] made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]A
[normal] special form of procedure based on section 16 of the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006. 
[normal]Introduction
[normal]321.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The purpose of clause 51 is to enable a Minister of the Crown to use delegated legislation to 
[normal]disapply
[normal] legislation – Acts of Parliament and subordinate legislation made under such Acts -  which is no longer of practical use, thus  rationalising the law. Clauses 54-56 provide safeguards for the use of the power, including the need for appropriate consultation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Devolution
[normal]322.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This
[normal] power is 
[normal]exercisable in relation to England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. As 
[normal]such 
[normal]it 
[normal]is capable of being used to 
[normal]disapply
[normal] legislation 
[normal]dealing with a matter 
[normal]which falls within the legislative competence 
[normal]of 
[normal] one
[normal] or more of 
[normal]the devolved 
[normal]legislatures. 
[normal]Where this is the case, and by virtue of clause 52, the Minister must obtain the consent of the relevant devolved administrations before making an 
[normal]order
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effe
[normal]ct of the provision
[normal]323.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This clause is intended to provide an accessible mechanism, distinct from, but supplementary to, the Law Commission’s Statute Law (Repeals) Acts and the mechanism provided by Part 1 of the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006, for removing legislation which is no longer of practical use. The main reasons are likely to be one or more of the following:-
[normal]Justifying the use of delegated legislation
[normal]324.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The use of delegated, rather than primary, legislation to 
[normal]disapply
[normal] legislation which is no longer of practical use will facilitate the removal of 
[normal]such  legislation
[normal], so that the statute book can be regularly rationalised in a way which is not unduly burdensome. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]325.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Law Commission is responsible for modernising and simplifying the statute book to make it more accessible to those who use the law. This responsibility is fulfilled through the Statute Law (Repeals) Bills which are introduced every 
[normal]there
[normal] or four years. The Scottish Law Commission and the Northern Ireland Law Commission have a similar remit. The reasons for using the power in clause 51 to 
[normal]disapply
[normal]  legislation which is no longer of practical use – which are indicated in paragraph 323 above - are similar to those which the Law Commission takes into account in the context of their repeals work.  However, the advantages of using clause 51 might include the following:-
[normal]Justifying the level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny 
[normal]326.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]department
[normal] recognises that it will be possible to use the power in a wide range of situations, and that the question of whether legislation continues to be of practical use does not invariably have an obvious answer. Therefore, the procedure sets down a number of safeguards which the Minister must observe in 
[normal]order
[normal] to proceed. These are as follows:- 
[normal]327.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is anticipated that each House will amend its standing 
[normal]order
[normal]s to deal with the procedure for reporting on draft 
[normal]order
[normal]s laid before Parliament under the new power. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]328.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The procedure is considered to provide adequate safeguards and an appropriate level of scrutiny for these 
[normal]order
[normal]s. It is based on section 16 of the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006 and, like that section, differs in important respects from the usual form of negative procedure under which an 
[normal]order
[normal] may be made but is subject to annulment. It provides for an 
[normal]order
[normal] to be laid in draft. It also provides that, if a committee of either House recommends that an 
[normal]order
[normal] in terms of the draft should not be made, the Minister will not be able to proceed with the making of the 
[normal]order
[normal] unless the committee’s recommendation is rejected by a resolution of that House. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]329.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Clauses 58 to 61 of the Bill contain two delegated powers.  The first power, in clause 59(1), enables a Minister of the Crown to specify, by 
[normal]order
[normal], the regulatory functions to which the duty to have regard to the desirability of promoting economic growth (clause 58) and the duty to have regard to any guidance issued (clause 60(4)) apply.  The second power, in clause 60(1), enables a Minister to issue, and from time to time revise, guidance in relation to the exercise of the growth duty.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Devolution
[normal]330.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The powers 
[normal]are  exercisable
[normal] in relation to 
[normal]England and Wales,
[normal] Scotland, and Northern Ireland
[normal] only in relation to matters which
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]are not
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]devolved Welsh matters or are not transferred to Northern Ireland, or which, as regards Scotland,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]are reserved.
[normal] There is an express carve out (in clause 59(3)) for devolved matters. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power exercised by: 
[normal]              
[normal]Order
[normal] made by statutory instrument
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]A
[normal]ffirmative 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]331.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The power in clause 59(1) enables a Minister of the Crown to specify, by 
[normal]order
[normal], which regulatory functions are those to which the growth duty in clause 58 and the duty to have regard to guidance in clause 60(4) apply.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]332.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The functions which can be specified by 
[normal]order
[normal] are those defined in clause 61.  They include functions exercisable by or on behalf of the Crown (clause 61(2)).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]333.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Before making an 
[normal]order
[normal] under clause 59, the Minister must consult any person whose functions are to be specified by 
[normal]order
[normal] and such other persons as he considers appropriate.  An 
[normal]order
[normal] made under this power must be made by statutory instrument and it is subject to affirmative procedure.
[normal]Justification
[normal] of the delegation
[normal]334.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is appropriate to specify regulatory functions by 
[normal]order
[normal] to allow flexibility to add or remove functions where a new regulator or new regulatory functions are created.
[normal]Justification 
[normal]of procedure 
[normal]and  p
[normal]recedent
[normal]335.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The procedural requirements for specifying regulatory functions that are subject to the growth duty are broadly similar to the requirements for specifying regulatory functions that are subject to the duty to have regard to the better regulations principles and a statutory code of practice which are set out in section 24 of the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006, namely that:
[normal]336.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]department
[normal] considers that clause 59 provides a significant safeguard in relation to the growth duty as it will provide Parliament with the opportunity to debate and approve which particular regulatory functions will be subject to the growth duty.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Power exercised by: 
[normal] 
[normal]              
[normal]I
[normal]ssuing guidance and bringing it into force by 
[normal]order
[normal] made by statutory instrument
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]Guidance may not be issued unless a draft has been laid before Parliament and approved by a resolution of each House; an order bringing the guidance into force is not subject to any parliamentary procedure
[normal] 
[normal]Introduction
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]337.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Clause 60(1) contains a power enabling a Minister of the Crown to issue from time to time guidance to which persons must have regard when exercising the growth duty 
[normal]under clause 58(1).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]338.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Clause 60(2) and (3) provide that this guidance may concern: 
[normal](a) 
[normal]              
[normal]the
[normal] meaning of economic growth;
[normal](b) 
[normal]              
[normal]the
[normal] ways in which regulatory functions may be exercised so as to promote economic growth; and 
[normal](c)
[normal]              
[normal]the
[normal] ways in which compliance with the growth duty can be demonstrated.
[normal]Justification
[normal] of the delegation
[normal]339.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is common for statutory guidance to be issued in a 
[normal]document  rather
[normal] than being set out in legislation, as this is more flexible.  It will enable the 
[normal]Government
[normal] to respond quickly to the experiences of those exercising the growth duty in practice and it will ensure that the guidance can be tailored to the needs of different sectors.  
[normal]Justification 
[normal]of procedure and p
[normal]recedent
[normal]340.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]department
[normal] recognises that the duty to have regard to the promotion of economic growth is potentially wide-ranging and there are therefore rigorous consultation and scrutiny requirements that will apply to the exercise of this power.   
[normal]341.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The procedural requirements for issuing guidance are substantially the same as the procedural requirements for issuing a statutory code of practice in relation to the exercise of specified regulatory functions which are set out at section 23 of the Legislative and Regulatory Reform Act 2006.  The requirements are that:
[normal]342.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]No parliamentary procedure is required for the making of an 
[normal]order
[normal] bringing the guidance into force. An 
[normal]order
[normal] bringing guidance into force is similar to a commencement 
[normal]order
[normal] and it is not usual for commencement 
[normal]order
[normal]s to be subject to parliamentary procedure.
[normal]Clause 62: consequential amendments, repeals and revocations [bold]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] 
[normal]Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by: 
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Order
[normal] made by statutory instrument
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]A
[normal]ffirmative for 
[normal]order
[normal]s which amend, repeal 
[normal]or  revoke
[normal]  any provision of primary legislation; negative for other 
[normal]order
[normal]s. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]343.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The purpose of clause 62 is to enable the Secretary of State to use delegated legislation to make such provision as is appropriate in consequence of the Act. Such provision may include transitional, transitory or saving provision, and amendments, repeals, revocations or other modifications of any provision of primary or subordinate legislation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]344.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This power is exercisable in relation to England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Devolution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]345.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This power is exercisable in relation to England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland and includes power to amend legislation passed or made by the devolved legislatures. Any amendments would, however, be consequential on other provisions of the Bill. Discussions as to whether a legislative consent motion is necessary are taking place.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]346.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This is a standard clause which provides a mechanism for amending legislation which needs to be changed in consequence of the Act. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justifying the use of delegated legislation
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]347.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Bill includes many of the consequential amendments of primary legislation that will be needed as a result of the substantive provision being made by the Bill, although some further consequential amendments of primary legislation may need to be made. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]348.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] In addition, consequential amendments of subordinate legislation will be needed.  It was decided that (in the majority of cases) it would be more appropriate to deal with these amendments through an 
[normal]order
[normal] making power, rather than on the face of the Bill.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justifying the level of p
[normal]arliamentary scrutiny 
[normal]349.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Where the 
[normal]order
[normal] making power is to be used 
[normal]to  amend
[normal], repeal or revoke primary legislation, the affirmative procedure was considered appropriate. This is in accordance with normal practice. In other cases, it was considered that the negative procedure is appropriate.  Clause 62 deals with changes which need to be made in consequence of the substantive provisions in the Bill. The policies behind the substantive provisions will already have been debated and approved. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Clause 64: Commencement[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Power conferred on
[normal]: 
[normal]              
[normal]The
[normal] Secretary of State
[normal]Power exercised by:
[normal]              
[normal]Order
[normal] 
[normal]made  by
[normal] statutory instrument
[normal]Parliamentary procedure: 
[normal]              
[normal]None
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]350.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Clause 64(4) provides that, unless otherwise specified by clause 64, the provisions of the Act will come into force on such day as the Secretary of State may by 
[normal]order
[normal] appoint. Clause 64(5) provides that an 
[normal]order
[normal] may appoint different days for different purposes. Clause 64(6) provides that the Secretary of State may by 
[normal]order
[normal] make such transitional, transitory or saving provision as he or she considers appropriate in connection with the coming into force of any provision of the Act.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]351.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This power is exercisable in relation to England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effect of the 
[normal]provision
[normal]352.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This is a standard clause which provides for the commencement by 
[normal]order
[normal] of provisions whose commencement dates cannot be identified on the face of the Act; and for any transitional, transitory or saving provision to be made in consequence of the commencement 
[normal]order
[normal] or in connection with the coming into force of a provision other than by a commencement 
[normal]order
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the delegation 
[normal]353.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]For various reasons it has not been possible to identify all commencement dates on the face of the Act. The use of delegated legislation allows for commencement at an appropriate time. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Justification of the level of Parliamentary Scrutiny
[normal]354.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is standard for commencement provision to be subject to no parliamentary procedure. The substantive policy will already have been debated and agreed. 
